<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, March 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli government decided Monday to continue
the massive military action launched Sunday in Lebanon to
retaliate the killing of four Israelis by Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a meeting of the Israeli government's
"kitchen cabinet," or inner cabinet, which comprises Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon and
Defense Minister Moshe Arens.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Netanyahu held further consultations with
the wider security cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Israel waged heavy shelling and large-scale air attacks on
Hezbollah guerrillas targets in south Lebanon Sunday after the
guerrillas detonated two roadside bombs, killing an Israeli
general, two soldiers and a journalist. (Israel-Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Taliban of Afghanistan
Monday described talks with the United Nations as highly
successful, saying the militia will provide full guarantee to the
U.N. staff if they resume relief work in the war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
"Talks with Brahimi were constructive. We have not only assured
full security to the U.N. staff on return to Afghanistan but will
also facilitate them to smoothly continue their activities," the
Taliban's chief representative in Pakistan Maulvi Saeed-ur-Rahman
Haqqani said.
</P>
<P>
Lakhdar Bahimi, U.N. special envoy on Afghanistan, visited
Kabul on Sunday and held talks with head of the Taliban interim
council Mulla Mohammad Rabbani and senior official responsible for
foreign affairs Mulla Hasan Akhund on his fresh peace initiative
and matters concerning security for the U.N. staff.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is seeking security guarantees for
international staff to return to Afghanistan. (Pakistan-Taliban)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji said today that he will
exchange views with American leaders on Sino-U. S. relations and
other international and regional issues of common concern during
his official visit to the United States this April.
</P>
<P>
He made this remark during a meeting with visiting U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said he will also contact people in various sectors during
his stay in the U.S. in a bid to increase mutual understanding
between the Chinese and American peoples, expand the consensus
between the two countries, and promote the healthy development of
Sino-U.S. ties on the basis of the three joint communiques signed
by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Albright told Zhu that the U.S. government and people are
looking forward to Zhu's trip in April. The U.S. side regards
mutual ties as very important, she noted.
</P>
<P>
U.S.-China relations have entered an important period, Albright
said, expressing the belief that Premier Zhu's U.S. tour will help
strengthen the consensus reached by the leaders of the two
countries, boost the development momentum of bilateral ties, and
promote bilateral relations in the direction of establishing a
constructive and strategic partnership. (China-Zhu-Albright)
</P>
</TEXT>
