<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Personal Income and Spending Rise in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. personal incomes increased
0.6 percent in January while personal spending rose 0.3 percent,
the Commerce Department reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The increase, the first in five years, reflected a robust start
for the economy in 1999, the Department said.
</P>
<P>
The income figures, particularly December's, were influenced by
a number of special factors. These included a decline in farm
subsidy payments in December following one-time payments in
November and cost-of-living increases in January for Social
Security recipients and federal employees.
</P>
<P>
The incomes, if excluding the special factors, grew solidly in
both months -- 0.3 percent in December and 0.5 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
The fact that personal incomes increased faster than personal
spending in January helped them record a positive savings rate for
only the second time in five months.
</P>
<P>
The key component of income -- wages and salaries -- rose 0.7
percent in January after increasing 0.4 percent the month before.
Government incomes surged 1.2 percent, reflecting the
cost-of-living increases. Income in services advanced 0.8 percent
while manufacturing incomes, hard hit of late by declines in
export sales, rose only 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Transfer payments such as Social Security also rose, as did
rental income as did business owners' income, rental income and
dividends. Personal interest income fell.
</P>
<P>
Spending during the month was led by a 0.8 percent increase in
services, followed by a 0.3 percent rise in purchases of
nondurable goods such as food and fuel, paper products and
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Spending on durable goods plunged 2.1 percent following a 3.3
percent surge in December, reflecting the pattern of auto buying.
</P>
</TEXT>
