<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC to Finance Regional Hotel Chain in Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) has invested 2.7 million U.S. dollars and
acquired a 21 percent stake in Global Hotels Development Group
Poland S.A. to develop a chain of Holiday Inn hotels in regional
cities of Poland, the IFC announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
IFC's total investment in the project will comprise 3.6 million
dollars in equity and 7.2 million dollars in long-term loans, as
part of a 43-million-dollar package for the first phase of the
chain's development.
</P>
<P>
According to the IFC, Global Hotels Development Group Poland
S.A. is a hotel management company established by Global Group of
Companies Sp.zo.o., the Polish Enterprise Fund, and private
investors. It was formed to open and operate 20 Holiday
Inn-franchised hotels in Poland over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Global Hotels opened its first Holiday Inn hotel in January
1999, in the center of Gdansk, Poland's main port city on the
Baltic Sea.
</P>
<P>
IFC Director for Central and Southern Europe Harold Rosen
said that the project is designed to encourage private investment
in Poland's regions and will help to overcome the shortage of
quality hotel accommodation outside of Warsaw, the capital city.
</P>
<P>
IFC, a member of the World Bank Group, has been investing in
Poland since 1988 and has approved investments of 556 million
dollars in equity and loans for 30 projects in sectors including
manufacturing, services and banking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
