<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RBI Decides to Lower Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India (RBI)
Monday announced measures to lower its short- and medium-term
interest rates following the suggestions made in the
just-presented new budget for 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
RBI reduced its cash reserve ratio (CRR) from 11 percent to
10.5 percent from March 13 releasing about 25 billion rupees (600
million U.S. dollars) to the banking system and cut the bank rate
from 9 percent to 8 percent from the close of business hours
Monday.
</P>
<P>
RBI Governor Bimal Jalan said that with a lower inflation rate
in recent weeks, slow credit off-take and a lower borrowing
program announced in the 1999-2000 budget, now conditions were
right for such a move.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the foreign exchange rate, Jalan said there is no
change at all in the RBI policy with regard to the management of
the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The RBI move was expected by bankers as indications were
provided in the finance minister's budget speech on February 27 to
the parliament here. Some commercial banks such as State Bank of
India and Bank of India have also announced their decision to
lower their lending rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
