<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba's Mediation Role to be Reviewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) allied forces in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) meeting in Kinshasa Monday will review
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba' s mediation role in the
conflict-torn country.
</P>
<P>
The allied leaders Jose Eduardo Dos Santos of Angola, Sam
Nujoma of Namibia and Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe are scheduled to
meet with their DRC counterpart Laurent Kabila, to review progress
in the peace process, the Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Foreign Minister Stan Mudenge Monday told Ziana in
Kinshasa that the four leaders' one-day summit would among other
issues "analyse the relationship between Angola and Zambia".
</P>
<P>
Chiluba was chosen as chairman of the SADC peace negotiation
effort to end the seven-month DRC war but Angola is now accusing
the Zambian government of supporting Unita rebels, a position that
compromises Chiluba' s supposed impartiality.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian leader has denied the allegations but with Dos
Santos adamant it appeared Mozambican President and SADC
Vice-chairman Joachim Chissano is wideny respected as neutral to
the DRC conflict, and is being encouraged to take over from the
Zambian leader.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge said the SADC allied leaders would also be briefed on
their forces progress on the war front as well as progress of the
regional and international efforts to end the war.
</P>
<P>
The DRC war began in August last year when Kabila expelled
Rwandan soldiers who had helped him oust Mobutu Sese Seko in May
1997. This angered Rwanda which together with Uganda have backed
the Congolese Tutsi rebels who are seeking to topple Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Kabila then sought SADC's help and Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe
 responded by deploying troops to fight on Kabila's side.
</P>
<P>
However, since peace efforts began last year, SADC allies have
been confined to the western part of the vast country while the
rebels have consolidated power in the east.
</P>
<P>
The flurry peace talks at regional and international level have
yielded nothing and the Kinshasa summit could come up with an
allied resolution to launch a massive onslaught on the rebels and
end the war once and for all, the Zimbabwe news Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
While there is general consensus that there should be a
cease-fire followed by a peace process and democratization of the
system of the government in the DRC, there are differences on how
all that could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
The allies also insist that peace talks only begin after Rwanda
and Uganda pulling out their forces first and an international
peace-keeping force deployed before they too can pull out their
armies.
</P>
<P>
The American and British governments are also in consultation
with the countries taking part in the DRC war trying to help in
seeking a solution with special envoys of both countries having
already visited some of the concerned countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
