<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aid Won't Solve All Zimbabwe's Issues: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Governor of Reserve Bank of
Zimbabwe Leornard Tsumba Monday said in Harare that people should
understand the money the government receives from international
financiers will not solve all the country's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Tsumba told a workshop on economic and business reporting that
once aid was received the onus lay with the government to manage
those funds wisely.
</P>
<P>
"People assume once the government gets the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank loans then all the problems are
solved," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We should not be so dependent on such measures as solutions;
these rest with us entirely," he said.
</P>
<P>
On whether the government was exerting any influence on central
bank policies, he said, "We have a considerable autonomy. We tell
the government what we want to do and they support us."
</P>
<P>
He projected that inflation would have dropped gradually from
its present 46 percent by year end.
</P>
<P>
He called on the government to tighten its fiscal policy in a
bid to beat inflation.
</P>
<P>
The five-day workshop being attended by journalists from
southern Africa was organized under the auspices of the Zimbabwean
chapter of the Commonwealth Press Union in conjunction with the
British Council in Harare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
