<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Police Criticized for "Inadequate" Race Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Police forces in England and Wales
were failing to eradicate racial prejudice in their ranks, a
government inspector's report said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report comes less than a week after an inquiry highlighted
"institutional racism" in London's Metropolitan Police following
the bungled investigation into the murder of black teenager
Stephen Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
"There are pockets of good practise, but generally there is
room for substantial improvement," said Dan Crompton, the report's
author, who investigated how forces have implemented 20
recommendations made by the inspectorate 16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw said the report underlined the need
to tackle racism as laid out by Sir William Macpherson in his
report on the Lawrence murder investigation last week.
</P>
<P>
The Macpherson report denounced the Metropolitan Police as
fundamentally racist for its handling of the investigation into
the death of 18-year-old Stephen Lawrence, stabbed to death by
white youths in 1993. No-one has been convicted of the crime.
</P>
<P>
After the Macpherson report, the government promised to broaden
anti-discrimination laws and make immediate changes in policing
methods.
</P>
<P>
Straw has already announced that officers will soon be liable
to criminal prosecution for discrimination when police forces are
brought under the Race Relations Act.
</P>
<P>
Metropolitan Police Commissioner Sir Paul Condon has revealed
plans to introduce tests for racism as well as launching a major
study of what the public look for from the police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates from Developing Countries Lead in Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Two candidates from the developing
countries are in the lead of a campaign for the new chief of the
World Trade Organization (WTO), trade officials said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
As of March 1, 118 out of the 134 WTO members have expressed
their preferences during the consultation process which has been
kept with the "utmost confidentiality".
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Supachai Panitchpakdi and Morocco's Hassan Abouyoub
have got support from 39 and 35 WTO members respectively as their
first preference. They are followed by Canada's Roy MacLaren (23)
and New Zealand's Mike Moore (21).
</P>
<P>
At the WTO General Council meeting on Monday, consultation
facilitator Swiss Ambassador William Rossier noted that regional
support for Abouyoub had increased and at the same time he had won
a significant support in another region of the world.
</P>
<P>
As of January 20, Abouyoub was in the second place with only 23
WTO members choosing as their first preference. Supachai was in
the first place with 40 members in favor of him.
</P>
<P>
At the General Council meeting on Monday, the WTO members have
also decided to put off the deadline of March 12 for the selection
of the organization's new chief till March 30.
</P>
<P>
The 134-member WTO has failed to meet at least three former
deadlines to reach consensus on who will succeed Renato Ruggiero
of Italy to be the next director-general.
</P>
<P>
Ruggiero has said that he would not run for the position again
when his term expires next April. 
