<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Increases 1.6 Percent in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department said
Monday that the strongest burst of highway and street building in
24 years pushed a 1.6 percent increase in construction spending in
January, the most in seven months.
</P>
<P>
Construction was led by a 5.9 percent jump in government
spending, the most in eight years, fueled by a 25.7 surge for
highways and streets. Residential construction increased 1.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Commercial construction, however, fell 1.1 percent, pulled down
by drops at factories and other industrial facilities and at
shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
The Department said early that personal incomes and personal
spending also increased in January.
</P>
<P>
Separately, the National Association of Purchasing Management
said Monay manufacturing activity surged higher in February,
reversing an eight-month decline, as production and orders for new
business improved significantly.  
