<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Attorney-General Elyakim
Rubinstein Monday asked the Supreme Court to reconsider its
decision over an American Jewish teenager suspected of murder,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
In the name of the state of Israel, Rubinstein made a plea
asking the court to "carry out another discussion" of its ruling
last Thursday on the case of 18-year-old Samuel Sheinbein.
</P>
<P>
Overturning a lower court's decision, the Supreme Court ruled
that Sheinbein, who is suspected of killing an acquaintance in
Maryland state in September 1997 before fleeing to Israel, could
not be extradited to the U.S. because he holds an Israeli
citizenship by birth.
</P>
<P>
Sheinbein claimed Israeli citizenship through his father, who
was born in pre-state Israel but settled down in the U.S. in
1952. Israeli laws bar citizens of Israel from being handed over
to foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno and other officials expressed
disappointment over the ruling of Israeli Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court, which made the controversial ruling by a
panel of five judges, can reopen deliberations with the
participation of a wider panel of judges. 
</P>
