<HEADLINE> German Inflation Remains Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Initial data for February indicate
that the long steady decline in prices in Germany has come to a
halt, but that inflation is still at an all-time low of 0.2
percent, a report of the German Federal Statistics Office said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Citing data from six states, the Office in Wiesbaden said
prices increased 0.2 percentage points from January to February
amid higher costs for package travel and holiday apartments.
</P>
<P>
The February rise ends a series of declining annual inflation
rates since April 1998 when inflation was measured at 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Also, import prices rose in February for the first time since
September 1997.
</P>
<P>
But despite the rise, the overall annual rate of inflation for
February remained at the all-time low of 0.2 percent, the office
said, basing its calculations on price data from the states of
Hessen, Bavaria, Baden-Wuerttemberg, North Rhine-Westfalia,
Brandenburg and Saxony.
</P>
<P>
The office's preliminary report was the first ever to include
data from the eastern German states of Brandenburg and Saxony. The
final price report for February for all 16 states plus Berlin will
be issued around mid-March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
