<HEADLINE> National Unity Govt Called for in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Falae told a press conference held here Monday that the
establishment of a national unity government had become compelling
because of alleged "monumental" rigging of the elections by the
victorious People's Democratic Party (PDP).
</P>
<P>
The APP has accused the PDP of electoral fraud, saying that the
results from Katsina, Kaduna, Rivers, Bauchi, Taraba and Niger
states showed about 75 percent turnout, which contradicted reports
of 20 percent voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
Falae, joint presidential candidate of the APP and the Alliance
for Democracy (AD), proposed that "The headship of that
government, composed of nominees of the AD, APP and PDP, should be
determined by consensus from within or outside the nominated
members of the said government."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the nominated members would constitute the
cabinet and perform the roles of the Federal Executive Council,
adding that all elected members at various levels should be sworn
in immediately so that they could perform their constitutional
role.
</P>
<P>
The results of the presidential election have reinforced the
belief that the "military is not in a position to conduct a truly
democratic election leading to the handing over of power to a
democratically elected government" in the country, said Falae who
was defeated in the Saturday election.
</P>
<P>
In separate statements issued in capital Abuja Monday, election
 observers were unanimous that Saturday's presidential election
was tainted by irregularities, but said they didn't have evidence
that they were enough to overwhelm the wishes of Nigerians as
expressed in the voting.
</P>
<P>
The statements were issued by the Commonwealth observer group,
the joint Carter Center and National Democratic Institute, the
European Union and the transitional monitoring group. 
</P>
