<HEADLINE> Candidates from Developing Countries Lead in Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Two candidates from the developing
countries are in the lead of a campaign for the new chief of the
World Trade Organization (WTO), trade officials said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
As of March 1, 118 out of the 134 WTO members have expressed
their preferences during the consultation process which has been
kept with the "utmost confidentiality".
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Supachai Panitchpakdi and Morocco's Hassan Abouyoub
have got support from 39 and 35 WTO members respectively as their
first preference. They are followed by Canada's Roy MacLaren (23)
and New Zealand's Mike Moore (21).
</P>
<P>
At the WTO General Council meeting on Monday, consultation
facilitator Swiss Ambassador William Rossier noted that regional
support for Abouyoub had increased and at the same time he had won
a significant support in another region of the world.
</P>
<P>
As of January 20, Abouyoub was in the second place with only 23
WTO members choosing as their first preference. Supachai was in
the first place with 40 members in favor of him.
</P>
<P>
At the General Council meeting on Monday, the WTO members have
also decided to put off the deadline of March 12 for the selection
of the organization's new chief till March 30.
</P>
<P>
The 134-member WTO has failed to meet at least three former
deadlines to reach consensus on who will succeed Renato Ruggiero
of Italy to be the next director-general.
</P>
<P>
Ruggiero has said that he would not run for the position again
when his term expires next April. 
</P>
