<HEADLINE> U.N. to Make Ottawa Convention Fully Effective </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a statement issued via his spokesman, Annan said, "Today
marks the entry into force of the Ottawa Convention banning
anti-personnel mines."
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations remains deeply engaged in the effort to
make this treaty fully effective, by assisting States in locating
and clearing these weapons," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"All around the world, the occasion is being marked by the
ringing of bells," the statement said, "To emphasize his personal
commitment to this cause, the Secretary-General will himself ring
the Peace Belll at U.N. Headquarters at one o'clock (EST) this
afternoon."
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the U.N. Headquarters on Monday morning,
Annan told reporters, "It's good to see it happen. It couldn't
have happened without the support and enthusiasm of grassroots
movements -- people around the world who work with governments and
NGOs -- to make this Convention come about."
</P>
<P>
On the U.S. non-entry into the convention, Annan said, "I hope
they will not be out of the Convention forever, and that in time
they will come aboard."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, as it enters into force, the Ottawa Convention
carried 133 signatures and 66 ratifications.
</P>
<P>
At present, the United Nations has mine action programs in 14
countries, seven of these are long established, while the other
7 are either new or in the process of being mounted. 
</P>
