<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Heading For Slower Wage Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Monetary Union
will increase price discipline, leading to wage moderation and
a reduction of wage differentials in its members, the Conference
Board, a U.S. prominent research group, said in a report Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Slower growth in wages combined with increased fiscal
policy competition among member states will support new business
opportunities and help to improve European labor market
participation rates," said Robert McGuckin, co-author of the
report and director of economic research at the Board.
</P>
<P>
The report said recent slackening in some countries'
restrictions on product markets will likely spread across the
region. Much of the new employment will be in the service
sector, but this expansion of the service sector will slow
productivity growth in Europe as previously unemployed low
skilled workers find work in relatively low productivity jobs,
it added.
</P>
<P>
"Despite slower productivity growth, increased participation
rates will improve per capita income levels across Europe,
which could create a wealthier European market for all types of
goods and services," said Bart van Ark, co-author of the report
and consulting director for the Board's international economic
research.
</P>
<P>
The report said since the official launch of the Euro in
January, this year, exchange rates between countries in the
EMU have become fixed and control over monetary policy has
shifted from the individual countries to the European
Central Bank. Individual countries will have fewer policy tools
to work with when they experience economic or political shocks
affecting their markets, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said the reduction in policy tools will place
great pressure for adjustments on European labor markets to
buffer the effects of these shocks. And the report predicts that
the EMU member countries will continue to be buffeted by diverse
economic disturbances.
</P>
<P>
The EMU currently includes most members of the 15 European
Union countries except Denmark, Sweden, the U.K. and Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-01 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
