<HEADLINE> Repairing Iraq-Turkey Pipeline Takes Time: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 1 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi Oil official said Monday
that the resumption of pumping Iraqi crude oil via the
Iraqi-Turkish pipeline will take some time after it was bombed by
the U.S. and British warplanes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
General Director of the Iraqi North Oil Company Talal Ashour
Kanan was quoted by the Iraqi News Agency as saying that repairs
should be done to the pipeline's sixth relay transmission station
which was severely damaged by U.S.-British bombs.
</P>
<P>
He said that pumping Iraqi crude oil to the southern Turkish
port of Ceyhan has been halted due to the damages.
</P>
<P>
Kanan said the the sixth relay transmission station is the
essential link in the control system operating the oil pipeline.
</P>
<P>
"This station is important and vital for the process of
pumping crude oil to Turkey, and it is impossible to pump without
it, (U.S.-British) bombardment has led to a complete devastation
to all thermal switches and control and communication systems,"
Kanan said.
</P>
<P>
He said that rehabilitating this station is impossible in the
present time due to the lack of necessary spare parts.
</P>
<P>
"But we shall try to find some partial solutions to resume
pomping oil," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday afternoon, U.S. and British warplanes patrolling the
northern no-fly zone reportedly bombed the pipeline, killing one
oil worker and injuring two oil observers.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said that there were no military sites near the destroyed
section of the pipeline, which is around 40 kilometers away from
the Iraqi northern city of Mosul.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Iraq has protested to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan over the U.S. and British attack on the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
This oil pipeline is the major channel to transfer Iraqi oil
abroad under the oil-for-food deal which allows Iraq to export 5.2
billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over six months to buy food and
medicine for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British warplanes patrolling the no-fly zones in Iraq
have intensified their bombardments on Iraqi targets this week.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed by the U.S.-led western allies
following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from
"Baghdad's suppression." 
</P>
</TEXT>
