<HEADLINE> Commission on Status of Women Holds Forty-third Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Commission on the Status of Women on Monday opened here its
forty-third session.
</P>
<P>
The session, from March 1-12, is scheduled to discuss women's
health and institutional mechanisms for the advancement of women.
</P>
<P>
Discussion on institutional mechanisms for the advancement
of women considers the role of national machineries in
mainstreaming gender in all programs and policies at the
national level.
</P>
<P>
During the session, the Commission will also discuss the
mainstreaming of a gender perspective into all policies and
programs in the United Nations system, the situation of
Palestinian women, the release of women and children taken hostage
in armed conflicts, improvement of the status of women in the
Secretariat, violence against women, the situation of older women
and the 1999 World Survey on the Role of Women in Development.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Commission on the Status of Women is the
international governmental advocate for equality between men and
women. As a subsidiary body of the United Nations Economic and
Social Council, it aims to support the equality goals of the UN
Charter.  
</P>
