<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netherlands to Enhance Ties with Poor Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands' Council of
Ministers has decided to concentrate the country's structural
bilateral aid on 19 developing countries in a bid "to enter into
what is intended to be a long-term development relationship with
these countries".
</P>
<P>
The Dutch Government Information Council said in a news release
available here on Monday that the developing countries included
Bangladesh, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Vietnam, India, Bolivia, Ghana,
Mali, Mozambique, Uganda, Yemen, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
According to Dutch Development Cooperation Minister Eveline
Herfkens, there are two reasons for concentrating aid on a smaller
group of countries. Firstly, there is a growing conviction at an
international level that aid only really reaches its target in
poor countries where the quality of administration and policy is
good, she said.
</P>
<P>
In the second place, the minister said, the Dutch
implementation capacity is too limited to enter into a lengthy and
comprehensive dialogue with the recipient nations.
</P>
<P>
Herfkens also said that the wishes and plans of the developing
countries concerned must be the key feature of this dialogue, and
the Netherlands will then consider how, as a donor, it can best
support their implementation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
