<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Frowns on Security Council Arms Banning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Parliament, the
House of People's Representatives Monday called on the United
Nations Security Council to reconsider its resolution 1227 which
bans states from selling arms to both Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council Adopted on February 10 resolution 1227
which " strongly urges all States to end immediately sales of arms
and munitions to Ethiopia and Eritrea".
</P>
<P>
In a nine-point resolution, the House considered resolution
1227 as " discriminatory, unfair and totally inappropriate",
according to the Ethiopian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The resolution accused the Security Council of having made an
"historic and grave mistake, reminiscent of the injustice done to
Ethiopia by the League of Nations, by equating the victim of
aggression with aggressor".
</P>
<P>
After Eritrea declared it accepts the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) agreement on the Ethio-Eritrean border conflict at the
weekend, the OAU has urged Ethiopia to stop the war starting
February 22 which has pushed 10 km into Eritrean territory over
the disputed Badme front.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, the House Monday
submitted its resolution to the United Nations Economic Commission
for Africa, charging Eritrea with "aggression against Ethiopia".
</P>
