<HEADLINE> Russian Foreign Trade Down by 17.6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia's foreign trade turnover
dropped 17.6 percent last year to 133.4 billion U.S. dollars, the
State Statistics Committee announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports, at 73.9 billion dollars, went down by
16.4 percent while imports decreased 19.1 percent to 59.5 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The committee attributed the dwindling trade turnover in 1998
to lower prices for energy, ferrous and non-ferrous metals in the
world market and the financial crisis that forced down imports of
consumer goods and medicines.
</P>
<P>
Russia's trade volume with countries outside the Commonwealth
of Independent States last year was 104.8 billion dollars, 16.7
percent less than the previous year, Itar-Tass reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
