<HEADLINE> Russia Vows to Control Food Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian Deputy Prime Minister
Gennady Kulik said here Monday that the government will exercise
"strict control" on foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
"Food prices are as important to the government as the
availability of foodstuffs on the market," said Kulik, who is in
charge of agriculture and related industries.
</P>
<P>
"The cabinet cannot disregard food prices as the minimum
required for subsistence has increased by almost 80 percent since
August 17," Kulik said, referring to the date when the previous
government of Sergei Kiriyenko moved to devalue the ruble.
</P>
<P>
The national currency has since dropped to almost 23 to the
U.S. dollar from the original rate of 6.3 to one dollar, a slump
of over 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kulik said priority will be given to regulating prices for
bread, dairy products and vegetable oil.
</P>
<P>
Russian producers must meet the citizens' minimal need in these
and other foodstuffs. Therefore, the government will "continue to
support the Russian producer," he said.
</P>
<P>
As compared with 1990, the per-capita consumption of meat and
dairy products has decreased "by approximately 40 percent" while
consumption of potatoes and bread "has somewhat increased," the
Interfax quoted Kulik as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Kulik noted that food prices in the country remain
"much lower than world prices and, on some foodstuffs, two or
three times lower."
</P>
<P>
The price for grain in Russia, for example, is 50-70 U.S.
dollars per ton as against the world market price of 110-120
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
