<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Personnel Mine Convention Enters into Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Ministers of Austria,
Canada, Mozambique, Norway and South Africa Monday welcomed the
entry into force of the Ottawa Convention, according to a release
by Foreign Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
The Convention on the Prohibition of the Use, Stockpiling,
Production and Transfer of Anti-Personnel(AP) Mines and on their
Destruction, commonly known as the Ottawa Convention, enters into
force on Monday, March 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Opened for signature in Ottawa on December 3, 1997, the
Convention has been among the fastest to enter into force of any
such international agreement. To date, 134 countries have signed
the Convention, and 65 have ratified.
</P>
<P>
In addition to banning the manufacture, storage, transfer and
use of anti-personnel(AP) mines, the Convention lays the
foundations for international co-operation in mine action efforts.
</P>
<P>
With its entry into force, the Convention has started the clock
for States Parties to comply with their obligations: stockpiles
must be destroyed within four years, and mined areas must be
cleared within ten.
</P>
<P>
Austria's Foreign Minister, Wolfgang Schussel, declared:"
Today, the total ban on anti-personnel mines has become a reality
under international law. This encourages us in the pursuit of our
common goal: no more mine victims."
</P>
<P>
Lloyd Axworthy, Canada's Minister of Foreign Affairs, noted
that the degree of international support for the ban is
significant. "The way the Convention was developed broke the
rules, and now the speed at which it has entered into force has
broken the records, while we celebrate this achievement, we must
remember that our objective remains: freedom from the terror of
mines. Canada will continue to work with its partners to achieve
this goal."
</P>
<P>
Knut Vollebaek, Norway's Foreign Minister said:" The Convention
provides the international community with a framework for
effectively resolving the tremendous humanitarian problems caused
by AP landmines. We must now respond in a co-ordinated and
integrated way, in order to free the world of these weapons within
a finite period."
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Foreign Minister, Alfred Nzo, welcomed the entry
into force of the Convention:" it will significantly contribute to
eradicating this scourge from the African continant, thereby
assisting the socio-economic advancement of its people who have
been so gravely afflicted by the use of these deadly weapons."
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Foreign Minister Leonardo Simao noted that the
Government and the people of Mozambique are honored to host the
First Meeting of States Parties and look forward to welcoming all
participants. "It is our earnest hope that the Maputo Meeting will
succeed in devising joint actions against anti-personnel mines."
</P>
<P>
The five Ministers called upon all countries to join them in
becoming States Parties to the Convention, and pledged to work
together to promote effective global mine action, said the
release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Defend Its Sovereignty: Chiluba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- One day after a series of bomb
explosions rocked the capital city of Lusaka, Zambian President
Frederick Chiluba said here Monday that Zambia will defend its
sovereignty from acts of terrorism, which he said are being
perpetuated by "foreign forces".
</P>
<P>
He made the statement after visiting Angolan embassy and four
other scenes, where the explosions occurred Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia is not interested in going to war with any
country and urged the world community to condemn the attacks in
the strongest terms.
</P>
<P>
"If any country is exporting violence and terrorism, we are not
 interested and we will defend ourselves. We will continue to be
clean and violence is not our character of politics," he said.
</P>
<P>
His government will thoroughly investigate the incidents and
has already contacted the Unites States and other countries to
help investigate the terrorist acts, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba castigated some politicians for being unpatriotic by
seemingly supporting allegations that Zambia is supplying arms to
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
He urged the politicians to put first the sovereignty and
integrity of their country and support the government of the day
in trying to resolve conflicts, especially in the face of the
threat of war.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Chiluba said Zambian embassy in Luanda, the capital
of Angola, is safe and his government is constantly in touch with
the embassy officials to monitor the security situation.
</P>
<P>
Lois Perdigao,charge d'affaires of the Angolan embassy, told
visiting Chiluba that the Angolan government has instructed the
embassy officials to cooperate with the Zambian government in the
investigations of the explosion, which left one Angolan security
officer dead and another wounded.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba visited Ibex Hill area where Zambia Electricity Supply
Corporation (ZESCO) pylons were uprooted by bombs and Chilanga
where the main pipe supplying water from Kafue to Lusaka was
damaged.
</P>
<P>
The president also visited Zambia Publishing House Flats and a
foot bridge near the downtown center, where bombs also exploded
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Recently Angola has repeatedly accused Zambia of supplying arms
to UNITA rebels and threatened to take military actions against
those countries including Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
