<HEADLINE> European Main Stock Markets Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets finished
deep in the red Monday owing to opening falls on Wall Street and
rising U.S. Treasury bond yields.
</P>
<P>
In London, shares in the FTSE 100 index of leading components
finished down of 114 points, or 1.8 percent at 6,061.
</P>
<P>
"People are starting to bond watch," said an equity dealer at a
UK brokerage. The 30-year Treasury long bond slumped more than a
point as investors reacted to more strong U.S. economic data.
</P>
<P>
Shares find it hard to make gains against rising bond yields --
higher bond yields result from lower bond prices which make bonds
more attractive to investors at the expense of shares.
</P>
<P>
German shares finished down as these overseas factors grabbed
traders' attention with little domestic news to move the market.
</P>
<P>
The leading Xetra Dax index finished down 125 points at 4,779,
a drop of 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
French stocks fell back sharply on the Wall Street sell-off.
The leading Cac 40 index closed down 61 points at 4,032.
</P>
<P>
Leading blue chip France Telecom lost 2 percent. Electrical
equipment maker Schneider was among the biggest losers following a
profit warning. 
</P>
