<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 21:00 GMT, March 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli government decided Monday to continue
the massive military action launched Sunday in Lebanon to
retaliate the killing of four Israelis by Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a meeting of the Israeli government's
"kitchen cabinet," or inner cabinet, which comprises Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon and
Defense Minister Moshe Arens.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Netanyahu held further consultations with
the wider security cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Israel waged heavy shelling and large-scale air attacks on
Hezbollah guerrillas targets in south Lebanon Sunday after the
guerrillas detonated two roadside bombs, killing an Israeli
general, two soldiers and a journalist. (BC-Israel-Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Two guerrillas of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or
Party of God, were killed in south Lebanon Sunday, Hezbollah
sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
They were killed during conflicts with Israeli forces in the
Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon, the sources said,
without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is leading a guerrilla war in the country trying to
oust Israeli forces from south Lebanon where the Jewish state set
up a self-declared security zone in 1985 to allegedly protect its
north from Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The fresh fatalities raised to five the number of Hezbollah
guerrillas killed in south Lebanon since the start of this year.
(BC-Lebanon-Hezbollah-Killed)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Amid Israeli threat to launch a full-scale offensive
against Lebanon, the country's anti-Israeli guerrillah group
Hezbollah, or Party of God, Monday vowed that it would not stop
attacks on Israeli forces in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"There are no obstacles which could deter us from launching
such operations in any circumstance and place, as that is our
legal right," Saayed Hassan Nasrallah, the head of the party, said
at a news conference in southern suburb of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Nasrallah's remarks came as Israel is threatening to launch a
sea, air and ground offensive against Hezbollah to avenge the
killing of four Israelis, including a general.
(BC-Lebanon-Hezbollah-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- An Iraqi Oil official said Monday that the
resumption of pumping Iraqi crude oil via the Iraqi-Turkish
pipeline will take some time after it was bombed by the U.S. and
British warplanes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
General Director of the Iraqi North Oil Company Talal Ashour
Kanan was quoted by the Iraqi News Agency as saying that repairs
should be done to the pipeline's sixth relay transmission station
which was severely damaged by U.S.-British bombs.
</P>
<P>
He said that pumping Iraqi crude oil to the southern Turkish
port of Ceyhan has been halted due to the damages.
</P>
<P>
Kanan said the the sixth relay transmission station is the
essential link in the control system operating the oil pipeline.
(BC-Iraq-Turkey-Oil Pipeline)


01/03/99 20:54 GMT

NNNN
04:56 04:56 g # PAB
