<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, S. African Officials Meet to Salvage Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 1 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) chief
negotiator Philip Lowe Monday met South African trade officials in
Pretoria in an attempt to get free trade talks back on track,
South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
A draft deal hammered out by South African Trade and Industry
Minister Alec Erwin and Joao de Deus Pinheiro, the EU commissioner
responsible for Africa, in Davos, Switzerland, in January was
rejected by five EU countries last week.
</P>
<P>
South African officials said Monday that a date had yet to be
set for a planned meeting between Erwin and Pinheiro.
</P>
<P>
Erwin has indicated South Africa's unwillingness to make any
more significant concessions to the EU.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of European parliamentarians visiting South Africa
on Monday expressed deep regret that ratification of the deal had
been delayed by the EU council of foreign ministers, according to
SAPA.
</P>
<P>
"The council has thrown a real spanner in the works. It should
not have happened," Terry Wynn, a delegation member, told the
trade committee of the South African National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"All we can say is that you still have a lot of friends who are
battling hard to make sure that this decision is overturned. And
it will be overturned."
</P>
<P>
Wynn said he had spoken to Pinheiro last Thursday, who was
confident that the outstanding issues could be resolved within a
month.
</P>
<P>
Wynn claimed it came as a shock to everyone -- other than the
five countries which objected to the Davos accord -- that the deal
had been blocked.
</P>
<P>
The five countries are France, Greece, Italy, Portugal and
Spain.
</P>
<P>
Hadar Cars, another delegation member, said: "It is one
country, and why not say it openly -- Spain -- that is the
problem.
</P>
<P>
"There must be some kind of pressure put on Spain... to find a
solution that is acceptable to Spain."
</P>
<P>
The South African parliamentarians expressed their anger and
disappointment at EU's failure to ratify the deal in strong terms.
</P>
<P>
Committee chairman Rob Davies said the chances of the deal
being passed by the country's first democratically elected
parliament were very slim as it was to be dissolved before the end
of the month.
</P>
<P>
The Davos accord envisions EU markets being opened to 95
percent of South African exports over a 10-year period, and South
Africa removing barriers to 86 percent of EU exports over 12
years.
</P>
<P>
The EU council of foreign minister is like to consider the deal
again on March 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
