<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Inflation Rate Down to Nine Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 2 (Xinhua) --Tanzania's inflation rate has
been brought down to the current nine percent from 27 percent four
years ago due to stringent monetary policies, Finance Minister
Daniel Yona has said.
</P>
<P>
Yona told a press conference Monday that such a progress has
been achieved mainly by controlling the government spending like
limiting official travels and seminars, an official statement said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The tax collection has also been improved from an average of 55
billion Tanzanian Shillings (one U.S. Dollar equals 690 Tanzanian
Shillings) to 60 billion Shillings per month, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yona said the government has introduced a "cash budget" system
under which every department limits its expenses to the amount it
earns.
</P>
<P>
"Stringency in the management of public funds has resulted in
stability of prices, a trend that was reflected in stability of
the local currency," he said.
</P>
<P>
On payment of the country's foreign debt that has accumulated
to nine billion Dollars, Yona explained that Tanzania would
continue meeting its due obligations in order to maintain
credibility among its creditors.
</P>
<P>
"We are forced to pay the debt because you can only borrow when
you are trustworthy," he said.
</P>
<P>
On domestic debts, the minister said the government has started
paying off but in installments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
