<HEADLINE> Canadian Economy Enjoys Mini-Boom in Fourth Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Canada's economy turned in one of
its best quarters of the decade during the last quarter of 1998,
Statistics Canada reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the gross domestic product (GDP) was twice as strong
as expected in December 1998, lifting the rate of growth in the
fourth quarter to 4.6 percent -- more than 2.5 times the rate in
the previous two quarters, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The year's strong close left the economy's growth rate for 1998
at 3 percent, down from 3.8 percent in 1997. Analysts here expect
a further slow-down this year, although no recession, and many
said the fourth-quarter mini-boom was less impressive than it
looked on the surface.
</P>
<P>
"It's not as good as the raw numbers suggest," Royal Bank of
Canada chief economist John McCallum said of the report. "But it'
s decent and it's consistent with a gradual slow-down in growth,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The fourth-quarter acceleration in production was largely auto-
related, and reflects not only a rebound effect from summer work
disruptions, but also a strong push to rebuild depleted
inventories in Canada and south of the border," said Statistics
Canada.
</P>
<P>
Canadian exports of motor vehicles soared nearly 25 percent in
the quarter, rallying back after summer factory shutdowns during
the General Motors Corp. strike in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
