<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Improve Ecology Along World's Second Longest Inland River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region in northwest China is planning to spend 1.5 billion yuan (
about 180 million U.S. dollars) on improving the ecological
environment of the Tarim River, the world's second longest inland
river.
</P>
<P>
"Once the project is accomplished, a green corridor stretching
more than 1,000 kilometers will appear along the Tarim River,
which might be the world's largest man-made oasis," said Xu Peng,
a professor with the Xinjiang University of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Xu, also deputy director of the Standing Committee of the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Regional People's Congress, is here to
attend the Second Session of the Ninth National People's Congress
(NPC), which is to open on March 5.
</P>
<P>
Running a total of 1,321 kilometers, the Tarim River flows
through Xinjiang, China's largest provincial-level administrative
region with an area of some 1.65 million square kilometers, one-
sixth of the country's total, and is regarded by the local people
as the region's "mother river."
</P>
<P>
In recent years, however, ecological conditions in the Tarim
River Basin kept deteriorating, as areas along the river's lower
reaches have been frequented by natural disasters ranging from
droughts and windstorms to sandstorms and frostbite. Areas along
the river's middle reaches are also under the threat of
desertification now.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that the annual water flow in the lower
reaches of the Tarim River has dropped to 289 million cubic meters
in the 1990s from 1.1 billion cubic meters in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the total area of poplar forests along the lower
reaches has dropped to 110,000 mu (about 7,000 hectares) now from
810,000 mu in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
According to the ecological improvement plan, five million mu
of poplar trees, bushes and grass will be planted along both banks
of the Tarim River, while another one million mu of land along the
river will be cultivated as either cotton fields or pastures.
</P>
<P>
"The project will be carried out by two phases, costing 300
million yuan and 1.2 billion yuan respectively," said Xu. "
Therefore, we're looking forward to possible assistance from the
international community," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
