<HEADLINE> Lesotho Army Chief Recalls Mutiny Ordeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho Defense Force (LDF)
chief Mekhula Mosakeng Tuesday recalled the ordeal of a mutiny by
five soldiers in September last year.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant-General Mosakeng was giving evidence in Maseru, the
capital, at the trial of 41 members of LDF facing charges of
mutiny, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
He said he and Brigadier Anthony Thibeli, brigade commander of
the defense force, were taken to the maximum security prison in
Maseru under military escort on September 11. They were locked up
in a cell and their rank insignia were removed.
</P>
<P>
Mosakeng said he was taken to Radio Lesotho under heavy armed
guard where he was forced to read out a statement stating that he
had dismissed some senior officers. He was also forced to announce
his resignation from the LDF, the court heard.
</P>
<P>
The commander said he was then taken to his home from where he
managed to flee the country four days later because his life was
threatened.
</P>
<P>
The hearing still continues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
