<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Says Israel Could Quit Lebanon in a Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said on Tuesday that Israel could get its troops out of
Lebanon within a year, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted Netanyahu as saying that he believes a
solution will be found to end Israel's 17-year military presence
in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon twice before setting up a self-styled
security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim to
protect its northern towns against cross-border attacks by
Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu did not make an iron-clad commitment that
the deadline would be met after one year.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's remarks came after Israel's opposition Labor Party
leader Ehud Barak promised Monday night that he would withdraw
Israeli soldiers by June 2000 if he won the coming elections on
May.
</P>
<P>
Barak told the Channel Two of Israel Television that "within a
year after the formation of a government led by me, I will bring
our boys home from Lebanon as part of an arrangement that will
ensure the security of the northern communities."
</P>
<P>
The tensions in south Lebanon have been escalated as seven
Israelis including a brigadier general were killed by the Shiite
Muslim guerrilla group Hezbollah in the past week.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes attacked Hezbollah targets on Sunday night
in what Netanyahu described as part of a new, tougher policy
toward the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
As Israeli soldiers suffered from frequent casualties during
the clashes with the guerrillas, there is a growing support in
the Israeli society to withdraw the troops unilaterally from
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu's government insisted that only after the
Lebanese government agreed to disarm Hezbollah and deploy its
troops in southern Lebanon to prevent cross-border attacks, Israel
would put its troops out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected the demand, insisting that Israel must
withdraw unconditionally as called for by the U.N. Security
Council Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
Israel had been defying the U.N. resolution for almost 20 years
until it decided last April to approve it. But the Netanyahu
government attached conditions to a real implementation of the
law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
