<HEADLINE> Hindu Festival of Color Celebrated in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- India's Hindu festival of color,
"Holi," one of the major festivals, was celebrated throughout the
country Tuesday with traditional festivities and color.
</P>
<P>
Holi revelers went around with color powder or colored water
smearing it on the faces of friends and sprinkling color water on
one another or passers-by in the street.
</P>
<P>
The festival of color, which also marks the end of the cold
winter, was also celebrated by people dancing to the tune of
percussion instruments amid cries of "Holi Hai." During this day,
officials go to see their seniors and leaders and friends meet one
another to exchange greetings and smear color on one another's
faces.
</P>
<P>
The festivities which got under way last night with lighting of
bonfires to burn "Holika," the evil spirit, reached its peak
Tuesday morning. Notwithstanding the ban on throwing balloons
filled with colored water, passers-by became victims of children's
pranks and bucketful of water thrown from rooftop.
</P>
<P>
Police maintained a strict vigil on Holi revelers to check
hooliganism during the festival.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday is national holiday with all the shops and offices
closed. Most city public buses remained off the road leaving the
streets free for revelers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
