<HEADLINE> Chinese-Constructed Mosque Extension Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Upon completion of its renovation
and extension, the Jamia Mosque in the downtown of Kenya's
capital becomes the largest mosque in East Africa, which opened to
worshippers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new extension was officially opened by Abdullah Bin Sultan
Al- Dhaheri, Director-General of the Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahaya
Charitable and Humanitarian Foundation, United Arab Emirates, who
is the sponsor and financier of this project.
</P>
<P>
Several thousands of local Muslims attended Tuesday's opening
ceremony of the mosque.
</P>
<P>
The extension, at a cost of 240 million Shillings (some four
million U. S. Dollars), was completed by China's Sichuan
International Corporation Company Ltd. (SIETCO) in a record 690
days.
</P>
<P>
The Jamia Mosque, built in 1925 by the Muslim community, has in
recent years failed to accommodate the ever-increasing number of
worshippers. Many of the Muslims had to pray out in the open.
</P>
<P>
The new extension with a floor space of over 8,000 square
meters can now accommodate over 8,000 worshippers at a time. It
consists of the 1,680-square-meter main prayer hall on the ground
floor and the 1,080- square-meter hall for ladies prayer on the
upper floor.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the extension provides adequate space for
administration offices,lecture rooms, a modern library hall,
classrooms and a parking bay.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Jamia Mosque Committee said that with the
 extension completed, the mosque, as an Islamic institution for
various Islamic activities, would find it much easier to conduct
its activities more efficiently and effectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
