<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Put 25 Lots of Land for Sale in 1999-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government will
put up about 25 lots of land for sale by auction or tender in the
coming financial year after a land sale suspension of more than
half a year, an official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meet-the-media session, Robert Pope, director of
Lands, said: "In parallel, we will introduce an Application List
of sites which could be made available over the same period
through to March 2000. By this means, I believe that land supply
can be flexible in order to maintain stability."
</P>
<P>
Despite the land sale suspension from June last year, the Lands
Department received a total of about 20 billion HK dollars (2.56
billion U.S. dollars) in premiums from land transactions in 1998
including lease modifications, land exchanges and private treaty
grants, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government expects revenue from land sales in 1999/2000 to
be 30.8 billion HK dollars (3.95 billion U.S. dollars) in the
coming financial year beginning April.
</P>
<P>
Pope said prior to the suspension, the department sold 10 sites
for housing, one site for a film studio and three sites for the
Private Sector Participation Scheme.
</P>
<P>
In addition, seven sites were granted for the Home Ownership
Scheme, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
