<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Group Peace Talks Scheduled in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Formal peace talks between the
Philippine government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
will be held in May following a coordinating meeting this month, a
senior government official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando S. Mercado told reporters that no
venue of the formal talks has been agreed on but the government
has been consistent that talks with the MILF will be held "within
the territorial limits" of the country.
</P>
<P>
He brushed aside the suggestion that talks be held in a foreign
country, saying the MILF case is different from that of the Moro
National Liberation Front (MNLF) wherein the Organization of the
Islamic Conference was involved.
</P>
<P>
Mercado said the preliminary meeting on March 25 and 26, during
which the most difficult and thorny questions will be resolved, is
vital before the formal talks.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a splinter group of the larger MNLF, is fighting for
an independent Islamic state which the government has rejected.
</P>
<P>
Heavy fighting broke out last month between government forces
and the MILF. But before the fighting spread further, the two
sides signed a new cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
A meeting between Philippine President Joseph E. Estrada and
MILF Chairman Hashim Salamat scheduled for last Sunday was
canceled due to disagreement on security measures and the venue,
government officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
