<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks in Vietnam Welcome New Forex Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- With foreign exchange reserves of
around 600 million U.S. dollars, Vietnam's central bank is strong
enough to intervene should any abrupt fluctuations occur, The
Saigon Times daily Tuesday quoted a banking official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Bankers said setting rates by averaging the previous working
day's transactions rather than imposing spot rates is a step
toward full convertibility of the country's currency, the dong.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Director of Vietcombank in Ho Chi Minh City Truong Van
Phuoc said, "The market aspect has been included in foreign
exchange more than ever before."
</P>
<P>
According to the English-language daily, bank executives said
following the announcement of the new rules late last week that
the Vietnamese central bank's decision to adopt more
market-oriented forex rules had been taken just at the right time.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that after the last adjustment in August, now is
the time when the forex supply-demand situation is most stable,
the executives said. Never before had commercial banks seen their
buying outstrip selling so much, resulting in mounting forex
reserves.
</P>
<P>
Daily spot quotations at commercial banks since last Friday
have been determined by adding at most 0.1 percent of the previous
working day's average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
