<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Air Force Helping Free Yellow River Of Ice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, March 2 (Xinhua) --The Chinese air force is helping
look for ways to free the Yellow River of ice that has been
blocking it mainly in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, north
China.
</P>
<P>
Unlike western countries, where icebreakers are used to cut
through the ice, China has been using planes to bombard the ice on
the Yellow River since the 1950s because the river, which is the
country's second longest and muddiest, has a great deal of silting
and icebreakers can't be used. This morning, a Yun-5 plane made a
reconnaissance run to take a look at the frozen section to decide
on further action.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, about 52,000 people in Inner
Mongolia have formed rescue teams to reduce the ice menace on the
river during the thaw season. Material and equipment have been
made ready for rescue work in case the situation turns dangerous.
</P>
<P>
In January, the Yellow River froze along a 750-km stretch in
Inner Mongolia and the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, and it
started to thaw late last month, so, engineers from the Liujiaxia
Reservoir upstream slowed the water flow starting February 22, and
the Wanjiazhai Reservoir, downstream, has increased its water
discharge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Inflation Rate on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Financial analysts believe that
inflation rate in Nigeria will go higher in the first quarter of
this year as compared to the 10 percent in December last year.
</P>
<P>
Since June last year, Nigeria's inflation rate has continued a
slow but steady rise up the scale, and it is the first time the
rate is attaining two digits points since 1997, the Post Express
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Coupled with the energy crisis, economy analysts said the
rising trend is likely to be maintained in the subsequent months
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The regime of General Abdulsalami Abubakar has promised to keep
down the spiral, but recent trends are indications that the rate
will definitely rise clearly above single digit for the rest of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The recent activities of politicians who released funds in the
banks into the public hands during the presidential election
campaign in the country will further compound pressure on the
inflationary rate, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
With the activities of politicians and othez cost-inducing
developments in the process of democracy, analysts believe that
the inflation rate would continue to go up this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
