<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infrastructure to Spark Next Asian Crisis: Keating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Asia would face a deeper
financial crisis as it built up infrastructure during its recovery
from the current economic downturn, former Australian Prime
Minister Paul Keating said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the fresh crisis would only be reduced if
governments heeded the lessons of the current downturn, he was
quoted by Australian Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Keating made the comments while giving his address Tuesday
afternoon to 600 civic and private sector leaders at the Second
Asia Pacific Cities Summit which is being held from February 28 to
March 3 in Brisbane, East Australia.
</P>
<P>
"This recession has simply delayed for a couple of years the
deeper Asian crisis and that's the real one, which the recovery
will bring on again," Keating said.
</P>
<P>
"And that's the crisis of funding and the building of
infrastructure ... required to support more than 2 billion people,
to feed and educate them and then to deal with profound
environmental consequences of that growth."
</P>
<P>
Keating said the growth and development would bring new
environmental problems including air pollution, deteriorating soil
quality and water shortages.
</P>
<P>
"No one can avoid the fact that the environmental challenge
facing Asia is real and pressing," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Asian governments are beginning to recognize that the
protection of the environment in the Asia Pacific is not an
alternative for economic growth but ... the only thing that will
actually guarantee its continuation.
</P>
<P>
"The next Asian economic crisis can be ameliorated but not
avoided, but only if national and municipal governments start
planning now, and if they draw the right lessons from the current
crisis about the importance of greater transparency and more
productive investment decisions -- in other words, fewer shopping
malls and more public transport," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
