<HEADLINE> CPPCC Members, NPC Deputies in HK Leave for Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong members of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC) and deputies to China's National People's
Congress (NPC) left here for Beijing by air Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They will attend the Second Plenary Session of the Ninth CPPCC
National Committee and the Second Plenary Session of the Ninth NPC
to be opened on Wednesday and Friday separately.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Beijing, Lee Cho Jat, a CPPCC National
Committee member from the industrial and commercial sector, said
that the "one country, two systems" principle has been
successfully implemented in Hong Kong over the past 20 months and
more.
</P>
<P>
"I will discuss with members from the inland areas how to
understand this theory in a more comprehensive and systematic way,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Wu, who has invested hundreds of millions of HK dollars
in the inland infrastructural undertakings, said he was encouraged
by the strong development of the economy of China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
Investments in infrastructure have low returns, but they are
very important because these projects have promoted the economic
and trade links between Hong Kong and the mainland, Wu said. "I
will continue my investment in this area," he added.
</P>
<P>
David Chu, Chairman of the Hong Kong Happy Valley Athletic
Association, said he will try his best to promote the
industrialization process in China's physical culture. "Resources
in this area should be fully tapped so that China's physical
culture will better go into the market and provide more job
opportunities," he said.
</P>
<P>
President of the Hong Kong Baptist University Daniel Tse said
that he will try to promote cooperation between inland areas and
Hong Kong in traditional Chinese medicines and pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
NPC deputy Tam Wai-chu said that the past year was a difficult
year for Hong Kong and the support from the Central Government is
very important for the development of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
She said that as a deputy from the HKSAR, she will try her best
to promote and coordinate cooperation between Hong Kong and the
mainland in high-tech area.
</P>
<P>
As a barrister, Tam said she paid close attention to the
legislative development in China. She would discuss the newly
approved Contract Law and the Securities Law with her mainland
counterparts for they are very important laws for China's economic
and financial reforms, Tam said.
</P>
<P>
Another NPC deputy Priscilla Lau Pui-king, a business professor,
said that she will focus her topic on China's economic and
financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
"I will suggest that China's economic and financial policies
should adjust according to the changes of the global as well as
the regional economic and financial situation," Lau said.
</P>
<P>
NPC deputy Cheng Yiu Tong said that during the 20 months since
Hong Kong returned to China, the Central Government has committed
to its promises to the SAR and has never interfered in the affairs
which are within the autonomy of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
He said that as a HKSAR deputy to the NPC, he will try to
enhance the contact, communication and understanding between
people from the SAR and the mainland. He suggested that a regular
communication mechanism should be established between the mainland
and the SAR.
</P>
<P>
A total of 79 out of the 158 CPPCC members and 22 out of the 35
NPC deputies from the SAR left for Beijing Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
