<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Trades Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar survived a
widening current account deficit Tuesday to end a quarter of a
U.S. cent higher.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar took heart from stronger-than-expected
retail sales data and traded to a high of 62.13 U.S. cents after
the data released.
</P>
<P>
By the close here it was buying 62.08 U.S. cents from 61.83
late Monday.
</P>
<P>
"A widening current account deficit and deteriorating
international investment position should add further to the
negative sentiment bearing down on the Australian dollar at
present," Commonwealth Bank of Australia economist Michael Blythe
said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) reported the current
account deficit for the December quarter deteriorated to its worst
level on record.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted deficit widened to 7.968 billion
Australian dollars (4.94 billion dollars) from a revised 7.304
billion Australian dollars (4.52 billion dollars) deficit in the
September quarter.
</P>
<P>
The ABS also released retail trade and building approvals data,
Seasonally adjusted retail trade rose 5.2 percent in January,
after a fall of 2.1 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
On the cross rates, the Australian dollar was buying 0.5701
euro from 0.5608 and the euro was at 1.0890 from 1.1023 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was also buying 74.61 Japanese yen from
73.55 on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
