<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassy Resumes Full Operation in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The interim premises of the
United States Embassy in Tanzania was officially inaugurated
Tuesday, bringing the mission into full function since suspension
following a car-bomb attack in last August.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said in a message read by Thomas
Pickering, visiting U.S. under-secretary of state for political
affairs, that his government will further develop friendly
relations with Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"This inaugural ceremony symbolizes the deepening relationship
between the United States of America and Tanzania as well as
Africa," Pickering said, reading another message from the U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright who is currently visiting
China.
</P>
<P>
Pickering said no matter how long it takes, the United States
will try every means to bring to justice the perpetrators who
bombed the old U.S. embassy premises just a few blocks away on
August 7 last year, which killed 11 persons and injured more than
70 others.
</P>
<P>
Charles Stith, the U.S. ambassador to Tanzania, appreciated the
 Tanzanian government for supporting the establishment of the
interim chancery which has cost 10 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the U.S. embassy said the new premises is based
on a private compound in the Kinondoni area on a renting basis
until a permanent and more safe embassy premises is built in a few
years.
</P>
<P>
The under-secretary, who arrived here Monday night from Harare
where he held talks with Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe on
regional issues, went into talks with Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa and other leaders immediately after the function.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to discuss bilateral relations as well as the
conflicts in the Democratic Republic of Congo before departing for
Kenya later on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. government supports the peaceful solution to the
Congo war, urging all the warring parties to hold peaceful talks
and all the foreign troops withdraw from Congo," Pickering told
reporters. 
</P>
