<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tooth Decay Hits Epidemic Proportions in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Tooth decay is reaching epidemic
proportions in China with an estimated two billion teeth already
affected and with a staggering 76 percent of five year old
children suffering dental problems.
</P>
<P>
The startling figures have been revealed after a countrywide
oral health survey and now the National Committee for Oral Health
(NCOH) is calling for the launch of an immediate campaign to
enhance public awareness to stop the rot.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted among 140,000 people in 11 provinces
and municipalities in the 1995-1998 period.
</P>
<P>
According to the NCOH, which cooperated with the Ministry of
Health in carrying out the survey, it would take 290,000 dentists
an entire year to treat the affected teeth.
</P>
<P>
Ironically 80 percent of those surveyed said they brushed their
teeth at least once a day, often twice. But the NCOH says there
are probably not using the correct brushing methods which should
be adopted without delay. It also blames the lack of regular
dental check-ups and the use of other preventative measures.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of dental decay is on the rise in all of China's
main provinces and municipalities, except for Beijing, Shanghai,
Tianjin, Shandong, Sichuan and Hubei. The comparisons are made
against a similar survey in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Dental disease is posing a great threat to children's milk
teeth. according to statistics in the survey's report which
discovered that each five year old it examined had an average of 4.
5 decayed teeth.
</P>
<P>
Periodontic illnesses have now became the top oral health
problem for the Chinese people. Nearly 95 percent of adults were
found to have dental calculus, a major cause of periodontic
disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
