<HEADLINE> Iraqi Civilian Killed in U.S. Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 2 (Xinhua) -- A civilian was killed and nine
others injured Monday in the latest U.S.- British raids on
military and civilian targets in northern Iraq, the Iraqi News
Agency INA reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
INA quoted an unnamed Iraqi military spokesman as saying that
"enemy warplanes" carried out two raids on the residential quarter
of Ein Zala Oilfield in Neineva province, part of the no-fly zone
over northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The raids damaged a repeater station on the Iraqi-Turkish
pipeline and civil installations in addition to the human
casualties, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
But he added Iraqi air defense repulsed the enemy warplanes and
there has been semi-confirmed evidences that one of the jets was
hit.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British warplanes enforcing the no-fly zones in Iraq
have intensified their bombardments on Iraqi targets this week.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed by the U.S.-led western allies
following the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from
"Baghdad's suppression."
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the warplanes bombed the sixth relay station on the
Iraqi-Turkish oil pipeline, cutting the flow to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
About 50 percent of the Iraqi oil export under the
U.N. oil-for-food program is transferred through the Iraqi-Turkish
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal, implemented since November 1996, allowed
Iraq, which has been put under sanctions for over eight years, to
sell limited amounts of oil to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
