<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Gains 21b U.S. Dollars Surplus Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia last year gained a trade
surplus of 21.42 billion U.S. dollars from exports worth 48.84
billion dollars and imports worth only 27.42 billion dollars, head
of the Central Bureau of Statistics Sugito Suwito said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country earned 48.84 billion dollars from exporting 7.76
billion dollars worth of oil and gas and 41.08 billion dollars
worth of non-oil/gas products, Suwito told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, however, spent 27.42 billion dollars from importing
2.65 billion dollars worth of oil and gas and 24.77 billion
dollars worth of non-oil/gas products, Suwito said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that total exports in 1998 decreased 8.6 percent
compared to 1997, with oil/gas exports going down 33.24 percent
and non-oil/gas exports dropping 1.76 percent over the same
period.
</P>
<P>
Total imports in 1998, meanwhile, declined 34.2 percent
compared to 1997, with oil/gas imports sliding 32.37 percent and
non-oil/gas imports plummeting 34.39 percent over the same period,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Suwito attributed the decreasing value of both exports and
imports in 1998 to the monetary turmoil which hit Indonesia in
July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah plunged from 2,300 rupiah to the U.S.
dollar in mid-1997 to 16,000-17,000 rupiah to the U.S. dollar in
early 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The weakening of the rupiah against the dollar has caused the
decreasing value of Indonesia's exports and imports last year,
compared to the previous year," Suwito said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indonesia's inflation rate in February was 1.26
percent, lower than that of the January which recorded 2.97
percent, Suwito said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
