<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian FM Arrives in Kuwait to Resume Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister
Abdul Ilah Al-Khatib arrived here Tuesday for a two-day visit
aimed at restoring diplomatic ties with Kuwait that broke off
eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib made the visit at the invitation of his Kuwaiti
counterpart Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah, who had indicated that
the visit will settle all remaining issues affecting the
normalization of relations between the two Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib said in Amman Monday that his visit to the Gulf
emirate will "set the ball rolling for the return of the relations
to normal."
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that the tour will be a chance to
exchange views with Kuwaiti officials on various subjects.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day stay, Al-Khatib will meet Kuwaiti Emir Jaber
Al-ahmed Al-Sabah to convey him a message from Jordan's King
Abdullah Bin Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The message is believed to touch on issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib is also scheduled to attend the reopening ceremony of
the Jordanian Embassy in Kuwait Wednesday, which will mark the
full normalization of diplomatic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Kuwait and Jordan deteriorated sharply
following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in August 1990 when Jordan
was accused of supporting Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's embassy in Kuwait was closed after 1991 Gulf War,
which ended Iraq's seven-month occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
A rapprochement process began in May 1997 when Kuwait declared
it "likes to improve ties with all Arab countries except Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Since then the two countries have exchanged a number of middle
and high-level visits, including a trip by Kuwaiti Crown Prince
and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad to Amman early February to attend
the funeral of Jordan's late King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Jordan are also moving closer in the economic ties.
</P>
<P>
A Jordanian Trade and Economy Ministry official said Monday
that the revival of economic and trade protocol between the two
states has reduced taxes and customs on the exchanged products by
100 percent since 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
