<HEADLINE> SADC Allies in DRC to Step up Offensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) allies fighting in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) have indicated that they will step up their offensive
in the east of the country while giving material support to the
Angolan government fighting UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the allied nations, Angola's Jose Eduardo dos
Santos, Namibia' s Sam Nujoma, DRC's Laurent Kabila and Zimbabwe's
Robert Mugabe, Monday held a five-hour closed door summit in
Kinshasa "to review progress in efforts to end the DRC war and the
situation in Angola", the Zimbabwe News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After the summit, the group's spokesperson and Zimbabwean
President Mugabe said the allies were not happy with the lack of
progress in peace efforts for ending conflicts in the DRC and
Angola.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the allies had "reviewed ways to end the two
conflicts effectively" within their mandate as SADC members
responding to distress calls by fellow members of the community.
</P>
<P>
He said allied forces were disappointed with the rebels and
their backers Rwanda and Uganda who had reneged "in a very
disgraceful manner" on every effort to end the conflict
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt on our part that Rwanda and Uganda intend
the war and their occupation of eastern Congo to continue while
they exploit the country's resources," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the international community to pressurize the two
countries to move out of the DRC because in terms of the United
Nations and the Organization of African Unity charters, they are
aggressors.
</P>
<P>
"We have come to a conclusion that we cannot allow their
aggression to continue. We have been reviewing ways to end the
aggression effectively," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
In fact, sources close to the talks said as the leaders talked,
their forces could have begun launching an offensive on the rebels
to recapture DRC territory now under rebel control in the east,
the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The allied forces offensive that was swift in the west when the
DRC war began last August, had been halted halfway to the east
when a flurry of mediation efforts began to end the war through
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
But numerous regional and international peace efforts have
failed to yield any results mostly because some of the individuals
championing a negotiated settlement have had their neutrality
questioned.
</P>
<P>
The latest such case is that of SADC's chosen mediator, Zambian
leader Frederick Chiluba whose government is now accused of
supporting the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) rebels in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe did not refer to Chiluba's case at the press briefing,
but Zimbabwean Foreign Minister Stan Mudenge had earlier said the
summit would "analyse the relationship between Angola and Zambia."
</P>
<P>
After being briefed of the situation in Angola, Mugabe said the
allied leaders were considering material support for the Angolan
government under the auspices of SADC.
</P>
<P>
He, however, did not say what material will be given to Angola,
when and how. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
