<HEADLINE> Thai NPLs Constitute 45.9 Pct of Total Loans: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Non-performing loans (NPL) at Thai
financial institutions in 1998 stood at 2.73 trillion baht (73
billion U.S. dollars) in 1998, or 49.5 percent of total loans,
Central Bank said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
NPLs were defined as debts at least three months overdue, Bank
of Thailand Deputy Governor Kitti Patpongpibul said. Total loans
were worth 5.94 trillion baht (160 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The total NPLs included those of foreign banks and finance
companies.
</P>
<P>
Foreign banks recorded NPLs of 9.96 percent of their 75.23
billion baht (2 billion dollars) in total loans while NPLs of
eight Thai private banks stood at 42.19 percent of their total
lending of 3.1 trillion baht (83 billion dollars) at the end of
1998.
</P>
<P>
The group of recently nationalized banks had NPLs amounting to
62.5 percent of their total loans of 1.7 trillion baht (45 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Thailand last year announced sweeping reforms designed to
protect the industry from future financial crisis. Thai banks are
struggling to recapitalize to meet tough new provisioning and loan
classifications rules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
