<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams U.S., Britain for Intercepting Ships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has accused U.S. and British
forces in the Gulf of intercepting merchant ships heading for Iraq.
the Al-Ittehad weekly reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Crews working on these ships said American and British soldiers
intercepted and checked the ships in the name of checking "acts of
terrorism," and intimidated the crew with weapons.
</P>
<P>
Hameed Thamir Hlaihil, director of Um Qasr harbour, was quoted
by the weekly as saying the "piracies" on the U.S. and British
part violate the United Nations Charter.
</P>
<P>
Crews said American and British soldiers messed up the cargos,
deliberately threw some commodities overboard and left the covers
of the containers open for long hours.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food program, Iraq is allowed to sell
limited amount of oil to buy food and medicine for its suffering
people.
</P>
<P>
Most of the contracted food and medicine arrive in Iraq from
sea route via the Gulf, where the United States and British
forces are stationed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
