<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Slip Lower in Light Volume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
slipped lower in light volume Tuesday as investors digested a glut
of economic news and company reports.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 18.3 points lower at 2,892.8,
with the fall spread across almost all sectors.
</P>
<P>
"The market does not know what to do, after being positive it
was negative and on that basis you would have to be optimistic
about tomorrow," Stuart Smith of Henderson Charlton Jones said.
</P>
<P>
"It was just an open the doors day in terms of volume," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The release of retail trade, building approval figures and
national accounts figures commanded the attention of the market.
</P>
<P>
Turnover for the day was 386.44 million shares traded at a
value of 1.091 billion Australian dollars (676.42 million U.S.
dollars), with 454 rises, 677 falls and 440 steady.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index dropped 34 points to 5,240.8, with
some noticeable falls among larger stocks.
</P>
<P>
ANZ was down 21 cents, while rival major bank Westpac gave up
12 cents.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank, which announced former Telstra chief
executive Frank Blount would join the board, dropped 20.8 cents,
while Commonwealth Bank bucked the trend to improve ten cents.
</P>
<P>
Of the telco leaders, Cable and Wireless Optus finished eight
cents lower and Telstra shed five cents.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was down 5.3 points to 961.2, with BHP
topping trade by value in an 11-cent fall, while Rio Tinto was
down five cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was down 17.9 points to 990.7 as the bullion
price fell 0.75 per ounce to 286.25 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
