<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Bankruptcy Filings Break Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, March 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 1.4 million
individuals and businesses filed for bankruptcy during 1998, a 2.7
percent increase over the previous year, a bankruptcy group said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The data, released by the Administrative Office of the U.S.
Courts, said personal filings in 1998 continue to drive the
increase, accounting for 1,398,182 filings, a 3.6 percent increase
from 1997 when filings totaled 1,350,118.
</P>
<P>
The number of business bankruptcy filings dropped 17 percent in
1998 to 44,367 from 54,027 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The third consecutive record year of bankruptcies correlates
closely with the increased debt load carried by American families,
" said Samuel Gerdano, executive director of the nonpartisan group
that tracks bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
Last week bipartisan members of U.S. congress introduced
legislation to reform current bankruptcy laws and curb the
increase in personal filings. The legislation would make it harder
for consumers to abandon their debts.
</P>
<P>
With the new Congress getting to work, some lawmakers and a
coalition of deep-picketed banks, credit card companies and retail-
business groups are gearing up again to push for enactment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
