<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lang Ping Quits Coaching for Healthy Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Volleyball Association
confirmed here Tuesday that Lang Ping has quitted her job as the
Chinese women's team coach due to healthy reasons for long-time
overwork.
</P>
<P>
Xu Li, Director of the Chinese Volleyball Management Center,
said today that former national team coach Hu Jin will step in to
take the helm of the women's squad.
</P>
<P>
He said Lang Ping, 39, whose health has been a vicitim of
overworking, was diagnosed as not fit to take on such high-
pressure job any longer after she underwent a physical check-up
early last year.
</P>
<P>
Lang Ping, who came to the rescue of the team four years ago,
shrugged off her poor healthy conditions to lead the restructured
national team to the runner-up of world championship in Japan at
the end of last year and regain the title of the Asian games.
</P>
<P>
After receiving Lang Ping's resignation, Xu said in view of her
healthy conditions, the association approved her retirement and
appointed Hu Jin to fill in the vacancy.
</P>
<P>
Lang Ping, well known as the "Iron Hammer" in the 80s, was the
key element of then high-flying Chinese women's team that took
four straight major world titles. The ace spiker retired from the
team in 1986 and went abroad to study while she played with an
Italian club and had a stint as the coach of the world all-star
team.
</P>
<P>
Giving up the better-off life abroad she came back home in 1995
as the national women's team has suffered a slump in international
competitions.
</P>
<P>
Under her guidance, the re-shuffled team also finished third in
the World Cup in 1995 in Japan and lifted the trophy at the Ninth
Asian Championship in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
