<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One of Phnom Penh's Casinos Closed by Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian government closed
a casino here Sunday night by order of Prime Minister Hun Sen,
local press reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I ordered one illegal casino in Phnom Penh to be closed down
before 11 p.m. tonight," Hun Sen was quoted by the Cambodian Daily
as telling the reporters at the airport Sunday afternoon when he
returned from Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The 24-hour-a-day, seven-day-a-week casino was located on the
third floor of the Hotel Inter-Continental. The one, once filled
with gamblers and guarded with metal detectors, now sits locked
and empty.
</P>
<P>
The government issued an order to crack down citywide on
illegal gambling two months ago, linking kidnapping in Cambodia's
capital to the prevalence of gambling.
</P>
<P>
Kidnapping has been a growing problem in the capital over the
past years, especially among the business and ethnic Chinese
community.
</P>
<P>
The city has also tried to crack down on illegal casino several
times in the past years. But until now the efforts have yielded no
results.
</P>
<P>
Two other casinos -- the Holiday International Casino and the
Naga Resorts Floating Casino -- still operate in Phnom Penh, but
they have been ordered to shut their doors by the end of June and
must relocate at least 200 kilometers away from the capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
