<HEADLINE> ASEAN-EU Meeting to Be Held Soon: Thai FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) and the European Union (EU) will soon hold their
delayed talks, Thailand's Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are about to solve the problems delaying the
Joint Cooperation Committee (JCC) meeting between ASEAN and EU,
Surin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Surin did not say exactly when the meeting would be held. But a
Thai Foreign Ministry source said it could be held in the next two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The EU is opposed to Myanmar's participation in the planned JCC
meeting which consequently has been canceled twice in November
1997 and January this year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar was admitted into ASEAN in 1997 despite strong
opposition from Western countries which accused the Myanmar
government of abusing human rights and harboring drug lords. As a
result, the EU bans entry visas for senior Myanmar officials and
generally refuses to accept their equal representation at
inter-government talks.
</P>
<P>
"We have new problem-solving measures and the meeting may be
held soon," Surin said.
</P>
<P>
He said preparations for an ASEAN-EU ministerial meeting
scheduled in Berlin, Germany, later this month were also being
obstructed by delays in the JCC meeting.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult to hold the ministerial meeting without the
meeting of the JCC," Surin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
