<HEADLINE> Kenyan Police Continue Search for Bhang Crops in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 2 (Xinhua) ---A police team at a town of Eastern
Province returned to the interior of Mount Kenya forest Monday to
search clandestine bhang crops after its work was temporarily
called off two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The team's work, composed of 40 administrative police officers,
will cover 38,000 acres of dense forest land at altitudes of up to
2,400 meters above sea level, the Kenya Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to boost the search exercise, police commanders have
asked for helicopters which are not available, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, the exercise was temporarily called off after
they failed to approach the dense sections of the forest where the
plantations are located.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Minister of State Marsden Madoka has expressed concern
that Kenya lacks adequate resources to reinforce the combat
against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, police destroyed eight acres of cannabis sativa
cultivated on the rain-fed side of the forest overlooking Chuka
Town, bringing the acreage destroyed to 161, and arrested three
persons attending the crops.
</P>
<P>
The three arrests added up to 39 others apprehended by police
since the the illegal growing was first reported last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
