<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Launches National Organ Donation Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The establishment of the National
Association for Organ Donation has raised hopes that lists of
waiting recipients in Lebanon will shrink with the availability of
more body parts.
</P>
<P>
The association will work to raise public awareness in organ
donation and to ensure any donated organs are distributed without
discrimination, the local Daily Star reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the current system, transplant surgeons have been finding
it difficult to know where and what organs are available. The only
possible way for them is personal contacts in their own hospital
and other hospitals, which often compete each other for the organs.
</P>
<P>
"The association will set up a national registry of donors and
recipients so that they can be matched," said Mohammed Khalifeh,
an association member.
</P>
<P>
Increasingly, desperate patients are ignoring doctors' warnings
and traveling to Iraq or India where they can buy organs and
undergo transplants for about 10,000 U.S. dollars instead of
14,000 dollars charged in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The paper said only around 10 percent of patients needing
transplant in the country can receive organs from cadavers, as
opposed to 90 percent in Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Foreign Reserves Up to 55 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign currency
reserves hit 55.46 billion U.S. dollars in February, up 1.87
billion dollars from the previous month, the Bank of Korea Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The total official foreign reserves include deposits at
overseas branches of domestic banks.
</P>
<P>
The foreign currency holdings have continued its rise after
another current account surplus and additional inflow of foreign
capital by corporate and financial restructuring in February.
</P>
<P>
South Korean foreign currency reserves are expected to continue
in the first half of the year. In the second half, however, it
will slow down due to outstanding payments to creditors,
observers said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign currency reserves stood at seven billion dollars at
the peak of the crisis in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
In December 1997, South Korea borrowed 58 billion dollars from
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) after it was gripped by the
crisis caused by corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial
institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
