<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet's Stock Market Maturing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Norbu, a middle-aged Tibetan, goes
to the stock trading center in Lhasa, Tibet's capital, every day
to watch the fluctuations on a big screen as he prepares to enter
the market.
</P>
<P>
Norbuo just retired from his job at a ferrochrome mine in
southern Tibet and explains that bank interest rates are just too
low and buying some shares seems a better bet. His idea is
supported by his family.
</P>
<P>
He is one of about 12,000 investors in Tibet, with Tibetans
accounting for half and Han Chinese, the rest, according to Deng
Can, deputy-general director of the Lhasa Securities Company. The
stock market is playing an important role in promoting the local
economy, she says. So far, five major Tibetan enterprises have
floated shares on the local market.
</P>
<P>
With the increase in the number of investors, the securities
company plans to open offices in Shigaze and Shannan prefectures,
Deng says. There have been no illegal operations found since the
stock trading center opened five years ago and she attributes this
to the support given by the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges,
which supplied two million yuan worth of equipment in that time,
in addition to an increasing number of qualified personnel.
</P>
<P>
Deng says she is optimistic about the future of the local stock
market since the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress passed the Securities Law on December 29. It will take
effect on July 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
She says the prospects of the local stock market are good and
more Tibetans will become investors as the securities market
develops and incomes of urbanites in Tibet increase faster than
those of people in the interior. 
</P>
</TEXT>
