<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt. Places Hope on IMF Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
expressed the hope that the International Monetary Fund (IMF) will
soon resume the suspended loan as the two sides are holding talks
in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Progress made in Kenya's economic reforms may have restored the
lost donor confidence in the country, which caused the suspension
of the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) in 1997,
Kenyan Finance Minister Francis Masakhalia said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that the IMF technical team will notice the
development achieved. We are hopeful that the funds will resume,"
the minister said, adding that the government was on track in
economic reforms and toward recovery.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team arrived in Nairobi last week, which could be a
signal for foreign donors to help the country with funds. The
team is reviewing the implementation by the Kenyan government of
reforms agreed on by the IMF in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the IMF headquarters is satisfied with
Kenya's implementation of a tight monetary policy, which has led
to a resumption of investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring of the Kenya Posts and Telecommunications
Cooperation (KPTC) has remained one of the major areas of
contention between the Kenyan government and the IMF, said press
reports here.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has also demanded the formation of an independent and
creditable board for the Kenya Anti-Corruption Authority and the
speedy conclusion of the Goldenberg case, which involves an
alleged 5.8 billion Shillings (966 million U.S. Dollars) fraud
over false export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
