<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 788 Palestinians Stripped of Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel stripped 788
Palestinians of their residency in East Jerusalem in 1998 in what
the Palestinians call a campaign of "silent transfer."
</P>
<P>
Of the Palestinians stripped of residency, 441 cases came in
the last five months of the year, the local Haaretz daily reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz also quoted a government report as saying the Israeli
Interior Ministry issued 201 house demolition orders in East
Jerusalem last year and carried out nine of them.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem municipality issued its own house demolition
orders and had 13 houses demolished in both Jewish and Arab
sectors last year.
</P>
<P>
But according to the Committee Against House Demolition, an
Israeli activist group, a total of 35 houses were destroyed out of
600 demolition orders issued in 1998 in the Arab sector alone.
</P>
<P>
The committee said the high number of building violations in
East Jerusalem is an evidence of Israeli discrimination in issuing
building permits. Palestinians said it is extremely difficult for
them to get a permit.
</P>
<P>
The committee also said the Jerusalem municipality is
manipulating zoning laws to make it hard for Arab residents to
build houses, and has failed to to supply Arab neighborhoods with
adequate infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians has announced East Jerusalem, seized by Israel
in the 1967 Middle East war, as capital of a future Palestinian
state. Israel, however, claimed that the whole Jerusalem is its
eternal capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
