<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Exports Up 22 Percent in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' exports for
January 1999 increased by 22 percent to 2.581 billion U.S. dollars
from 2.115 billion dollars a year earlier, the Philippine National
Statistics Office said in a report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 2.581 billion dollars, exports of manufactured
goods accounted for 90.8 percent and were up by 29.5 percent from
a year earlier, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Agro-based products comprised the second major commodity group
with exports of 96.37 million dollars or 3.7 percent of the total.
Other major exports include special transactions, mineral
products, petroleum products and forest products.
</P>
<P>
Posting a 5-percent increase, sales to the United States
accounted for 29.4 percent of the total exports for the month.
Japan with a 14.2-percent share was the second biggest market and
Netherlands was third with 8 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, exports to some financial
crisis-struck Asian countries and regions increased sharply for
the month, with Malaysia registering a 203-percent increase to
175.97 million dollars and South Korea a 193-percent increase to
67.77 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country's total exports in 1998 went up 16.9 percent to
29.496 billion U.S. dollars as against 25.228 billion dollars
registered in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
