<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Cancer-Urban Residents Types of Cancer Changing in Urban China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The use of refrigerators in China'
s urban areas has brought down the incidence of esophagus cancer,
while the greater intake of low-fiber food has increased the risk
of colon cancer, according to the Cancer Research Institute of
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, the incidence of esophagus cancer has decreased 60
percent in the past 23 years between 1972 and 1994, but the
incidence of colon cancer and gallbladder cancer have both doubled
their 1973 levels.
</P>
<P>
This has a lot to do with lifestyle and eating habits that
change as living conditions improve, according to the institute.
</P>
<P>
Because refrigerators are more widely used, people can eat
fresh vegetables and meat instead of food preserved in salt, which
is thought to be related to cancer of the digestive tract.
</P>
<P>
And, the more sedentary life and lower intake of high-fiber
food like corn and millet or other coarse grains that were eaten
during hard times has increased the risk of colon and rectal
cancer.
</P>
<P>
Other cancers that are reported to be on the rise in Shanghai
include lung cancer in males and breast cancer in women. In spite
of a general decline in the number of cancer cases in Shanghai
from 1973 to 1994, cancer has replaced cerebral hemorrhage as the
No.1 killer in Chinese cities, claiming the lives of 135 of every
100,000 urbanities in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Supports Fight Against Drug Abuse in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has granted
the Zambian government 2.3 billion Kwacha (some one million U.S.
Dollars) for the country's drug demand reduction efforts during
the period of 1997-2001.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a workshop organized by the Drug Enforcemernt
Commission (DEC) here Monday, Zambian Minister of Home Affairs,
Katele Kalumba described as "strategic" the involvement of various
ministries in the reduction of the drug problem.
</P>
<P>
The speech was read by DEC's deputy permanent secretary, Katuta
Nsemukila, on behalf of kalumba.
</P>
<P>
Kalumba paid tribute to the EU for the overwhelming support it
is offering in providing the technical expertise in the research
exercise for the next six months.
</P>
<P>
He said that the involvement of ministries in the drug problem
aims to help improve the overall health and socio-economic
well-being of Zambians, Zambia Daily Mail reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry hopes to build and, or strengthen partnerships
with public agencies and non-governmental organizations involved
in drug abuse issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kalumba urged the research team to recommend appropriate
measures on how to combat the drug problem among the vulnerable
segments like the youth mostly out of formal education, street
children and orphans.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the EU representative Guy Rijcken said the EU was
happy to see what Zambia through the Home Affairs Ministry is
doing in the drug enforcement program.  
</P>
