<HEADLINE> Woman NPC Deputy Cares for Poor Home County </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- "I hope all the 280,000 country
fellows in my county could get well-off as early as possible,"
said Li Chunying, a woman deputy to the upcoming Second Session of
the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
"As an NPC deputy, I'm obliged to do something to help my
hometown get rid of poverty," added Li who arrived in Beijing
shortly.
</P>
<P>
The annual NPC session is scheduled to open on March 5 and will
last through March 15.
</P>
<P>
Li, a 35-year old restaurant owner from Zhangjiachuan County,
in northwest China's Gansu Province, said she will propose that
her county be included in the state-funded biological and
environmental development program.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiachuan County has suffered from droughts for the past
six years, she said, adding that if her proposal could be accepted,
it will give a strong boost to the development of the county.
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, Li opened the first private restaurant in the
county town and gained her fame ever since. "Now there are a dozen
private restaurants in the town and they are equipped with better
facilities than mine," she told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Li is a Hui woman and her family now leads a happy and affluent
life. Hui is one of the 55 ethnic groups in China.  Pointing
to her white cap, Li said it shows she is married. "Many Hui women
are now involved in private business in my hometown, and my
husband, a manager of a state business, has always been on my side
whatever I do, either as a private restaurant owner or as an NPC
deputy," she said.
</P>
<P>
As a private businesswoman, Li added, she is greatly encouraged
upon learning that one of the most major topics in the coming NPC
session this year is to discuss an amendment to the Constitution
and to allow different forms of ownership in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
