<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Handles World Issues in Light of U.N. Charter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 1 (Xinhua) -- China, which assumed U.N.
Security Council presidency Monday, will, in strict accordance
with the U.N. Charter, uphold justice and better the efficiency of
the 15-member body when addressing issues concerning international
peace and security within its month-long tenure.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, China's permanent representative to the United
Nations, told Chinese reporters Monday night that the Security
Council will have a very busy working program for March to handle
major issues of great concern to the international community.
</P>
<P>
"African issues will be high on the agenda of the Security
Council in this month," he said.
</P>
<P>
They include the armed conflicts between Ethiopia and Eritrea,
the Lockerbie issue, the conflicts in the Great Lakes and West
Africa regions, and the extension of the U.N. Observer Mission in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Security Council will also address the problem
of Kosovo, the Yugoslav province where ethnic Albanians make up
some 90 percent of the population, and the Iraqi crisis, on which
the U.N. has set up three panels to deal with issues including
disarmament and humanitarian affairs.
</P>
<P>
In order to seek proper solutions to these issues in the
Security Council, China will adhere to the following fundamental
positions:
</P>
<P>
First, China will handle various issues in strict accordance
with the U.N. Charter and in a fair and just manner. Qin said he
will play both the role of China's permanent representative to the
United Nations and that of the Security Council president for the
month of March.
</P>
<P>
"I will voice China's concerns over certain issues in my
capacity as the Chinese ambassador, and at the same time I will
also speak on the issues of common concern in my capacity as the
Council president," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
Second, China will adhere to principles, uphold justice,
sympathize with and support the stand of the developing countries,
and in particular give more attention to Africa, said the Chinese
envoy.
</P>
<P>
In handling African issues such as peace and development, he
said, there should be no place for "double standards". "We should
give as much attention to Africa as we give to other regions in
the world," he added.
</P>
<P>
Third, China will work hard to improve the transparency of the
Security Council, which is also a major part of the body's ongoing
reform drive.
</P>
<P>
"China, while assuming the Council presidency, will give prompt
briefing to all parties concerned, such as the president of the
General Assembly, regional groups sitting in the United Nations,
on where we are in the Security Council," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, China will actively promote peaceful settlement of
regional conflicts, such as the one between Eritrea and Ethiopia.
China will participate in helping the two Horn of African
countries to end the conflicts and realize peaceful co-existence.
</P>
<P>
Last, China will help strengthen the authority of the Security
Council in the maintenance of international peace and security,
Qin said.
</P>
<P>
Not long ago, some countries resorted to force or threatened to
use force against an independent and sovereign state without the
authorization of the Security Council, he complained.
</P>
<P>
Right now, he noted, the U.S.-led NATO is stepping up pressure
on Yugoslavia over the issue of Kosovo with the threat of the use
of force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
