<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Muslim Farmers Visit Mecca </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"My cherished dream will be realized soon," said 68-year-old Ma
excitedly, adding that although the journey will cost about 25,000
yuan, he can afford it.
</P>
<P>
The pilgrimage, known as hajj, is required to be made at least
once in a lifetime by every able-bodied Muslim who can afford it.
</P>
<P>
Ma explained that for him, in the past such a trip to Mecca was
unthinkable because of his modest earnings.
</P>
<P>
However, ever since the reform and opening policy adopted by
China in 1978, the living standard of Ma's five-member family has
been improving steadily. Now the annual income of the family
exceeds over 20,000 yuan apart from the farmland and livestock
they own.
</P>
<P>
Following in Ma's footsteps this year, 187 farmers with an
average age of 65 years from the autonomous region will travel to
the holy city at their own expense, with 19 of them from Xihaigu,
the poorest area in the region.
</P>
<P>
The grain output of the prefecture stood at 900 million
kilograms in 1998, a record high which enabled 250,000 more people
to receive adequate food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
Five of the prefecture's eight poverty-stricken counties at the
state level, including the Pengyang County, have been lifted out
of poverty. The average per capita income of farmers in these
counties exceeds 1,025 yuan. As a result, more Hui nationality
Muslims can afford to go to Mecca on a pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
There are 1.78 million Hui Muslims in the Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region, accounting for one-third of its total
population. Since 1978, 1,600 Muslims from the region have
traveled to Mecca at their own expense.
</P>
<P>
Bai Xiuhua, 62, from Dongta Township in Wuzhong City was the
only female to go to Mecca this year. She said: "Women of Hui
nationality used to be confined to home. It was unheard of them to
go to Mecca to perform in the past."
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Zhongxiao, Section Chief of the Islamic
Division of the region's Religious Bureau, 63 female Muslims will
go to Mecca this year, accounting for one-third of the country's
pilgrimage delegation.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, who is also the head of the delegation, said the local
government paid great attention to the work of the pilgrimage
every year. Interpreters and doctors were assigned to serve
members of the delegation to ensure the smooth development of the
pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985 when the Chinese government began to organize
delegations to Mecca, at the individual's own expense, over 50,000
Chinese Muslims had performed hajj in Mecca. This year, 2,000
Chinese Muslims will be joining the pilgrimage organized by the
Islamic Association of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
