<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Consumers Favor Major Brands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Famous brand-name products have
basically taken control of the Chinese marketplace and sales of
lesser known goods are dropping, according to the State Statistics
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
A recent market survey showed that 10 famous color TV brands
have 80.5 percent of the domestic market while the top ten washer
producers have 91.3 percent of the market, refrigerators, 91.6
percent, air conditioners, 76 percent, and video compact disk (VCD)
players, 81.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Many lesser known brands are running into difficulties and some
have faded from the scene. The survey found that, against this
backdrop, buying is concentrated on household electric appliances
that are under consumed.
</P>
<P>
A study of the country's major department stores has found a
large increase in sales of personal computers, fax machines, VCD
players, and air conditioners, and large-capacity refrigerators
and electric appliances show potential.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show 99.9 percent of consumer goods either
over-supplied or with supply and demand equal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans To Halt Pollution Before End Of Century (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- China plans to increase pollution
controls and ecological improvements this year to halt
environmental deterioration, according to Xie Zhenhua, director of
the State Environmental Protection Administration.
</P>
<P>
Xie told Xinhua in an interview that the fight against
pollution this year is very important to the country's
environmental improvement goals of the next century and that China
plans to stop environmental degradation and improve its
environment by 2010.
</P>
<P>
He explained that priority will be given to controlling
emissions and to seeing to it that all industries meet discharge
standards and all major cities meet environmental quality
standards by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The state will have a serious of policies for this drive, he
said, and local environmental protection departments have been
asked to increase law enforcement efforts.
</P>
<P>
China will begin an all-out battle against water and urban air
pollution this year and the government has asked all industries in
the Southwest in the Dianchi Lake valley to meet emission
standards before May 1, and polluters in the East in the Chaohu
Lake valley to do so before year's end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
