<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Government  to Sell HFCK Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is to offer
for sale of 30 million shares worth of 420 million Shillings (some
seven million U.S. Dollars) of the Housing Finance Company of
Kenya (HFCK) at the Nairobi Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Finance Minister Francis Masakhalia said here Monday
that the sale of the government-held shares would reduce
government share holding in the HFCK to just 4.4 percent of the
company's total share capital.
</P>
<P>
With the government shedding 30 million shares of the HFCK, the
public and private sectors will hold 65.2 percent of the company's
share capital while the Commonwealth Development Corporation holds
the rest of 30.4 percent, the state-run Kenya Times newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Masakhalia as saying that the sale
demonstrated the government's commitment to divesting its share
holding in commercial enterprises in an organized way through the
ongoing privatization program.
</P>
<P>
He urged the private sector to become more innovative in
mobilizing long- term savings from pension funds and other sources
and channel these funds into the housing sector.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Nairobi Stock Exchange, Jimna Mbaru, said that
54 percent of the HFCK's shares are now listed in the bourse
whereas other companies have less than 25 percent listed at the
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
