<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Efforts Needed to Stimulate Domestic Consumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese economists suggest that
simulative measures to lift consumption demand should be adopted
to ensure national economic growth this year in the wake of
sagging exports and weak domestic investments.
</P>
<P>
Today's Economic Daily quotes the unnamed group of experts as
saying that given the present situation, the level of consumer
demand will decide the growth pace of the national economy for the
current year.
</P>
<P>
However, they also note that various factors will be quite
likely to lead to a slowdown in the upward trend for consumer
demand during the year.
</P>
<P>
They point out the falling increase rate of family incomes and
the conspicuous gap in urban and rural income levels will
contribute to the slowdown in consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
Consumers are fully aware that reforms of housing, medical care
and social welfare will lead to increasing personal expenditures
in the future. Therefore, the natural response is to reduce
spending and increase savings.
</P>
<P>
Economists nonetheless put forward a number of measures to
offset pessimism regarding the possible success of stimulating
consumption during the year.
</P>
<P>
They suggest that measures should be taken to ensure long-term
sustainable income increases, especially those of rural consumers.
</P>
<P>
The taxation system must be improved to narrow the gap between
the rich and poor, and measures be taken to increase subsidies to
the lower-income groups so as to generate consumption demand from
them, according to economists.
</P>
<P>
They express hope that policy-makers will carefully consider
lowering the high cost of housing in order to stimulate consumer
demand.
</P>
<P>
Experts also suggest that highway construction and the
installation of power grids should be accelerated in both urban
and rural areas in order to make consumption more convenient.
</P>
<P>
They also say that irrational charges over automobile purchases
and extra fees extracted from extensive electricity users should
be revoked to encourage more spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
