<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rich Oil-Bearing Strata Found in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese geologists recently
drilled three test wells and discovered a rich oil- and gas-
bearing strata in the northern basin in east China's Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
The Xinzhu-1 Well has yielded two oil-bearing strata with a
total depth of 6.8 meters, as well as two gas-bearing strata with
a combined thickness of 15.6 meters. The region's verified gas
reserves of 10 billion cu.m. are equivalent to an oil field
capable of producing 10 million tons of oil.
</P>
<P>
Two other test wells -- Fa-2 and Sha-22 -- near Yangzhou have
also reportedly yielded promising traces of oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
Qian Ji, chief geologist at the Jiangsu Oil Field, said the two
Yangzhou wells will form the basis for the establishment of an oil
field with an annual production capacity of 10 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu, one of China's major developed areas, long suffers
from a deficiency of energy resources. The province produced one
million tons of crude oil in 1995 and has since increased its
output by 100,000 tons annually.
</P>
<P>
The new discoveries will play an important role in helping to
adjust Jiangsu's energy structure and promote economic development,
according to local officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
