<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 07:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Tax to Net Huge Sum for UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates is
expected to net 272 million dirhams (about 73.44 million dollars)
this year in huge custom duties on tobacco.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco tax revenues are forecast to increase to 303 million
dirhams (about 81.81 million dollars) next year, the Dubai-based
Khaleej Times daily reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco tax increased to 70 percent in April last year from 50
percent when the Federal Law No. 2 of 1998 was introduced.
</P>
<P>
The law stipulates that the tax will increase to 90 percent in
July this year, with a minimum of 72 dirhams (about 19.44
dollars) per 1,000 cigarettes, and finally to 100 percent in July
next year, with a minimum of 80 dirhams (about 21.6 dollars) per
1,000 cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states, which rank with
highest cigarette consumption levels in the world, have
introduced tougher laws and heavy duties on tobacco products with
the aim to discouraging smoking.
</P>
<P>
They have pledged to increase the customs tariffs on cigarettes
and tobacco imports to 100 percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to industry sources, the GCC countries import nearly
30 billion cigarettes a year worth over 800 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, the total sum of their revenues from duties
on cigarettes and tobacco is likely to exceed 1 billion dollars
compared with less than 100 million dollars in the
mid-80s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
