<HEADLINE> Officials Urge Auto Industry Conglomeration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- China's automobile manufacturing
industry must establish conglomerates in order to increase
competitiveness, according to today's overseas edition of People's
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Daily quoted high-ranking officials from the State
Administration of Machinery Industry as saying that conglomeration
will be essential for coping with price slashes resulting from the
introduction of zero tariffs when China joins the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
China's 200-odd automakers produced 1.6 million vehicles in
1998, a figure equal to the annual output of a medium-sized
automobile manufacturing plant in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Domestic research and development costs for a single new model
currently stands at 150 million US dollars. And yet, China
invested altogether 1.3 billion US dollars in its automobile
industry during the Ninth Five Year Plan Period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
The administration has drafted a plan to accelerate the
establishment of conglomerates in order to reverse the situation
where a large number of plants produce relative small quantity of
vehicles and have weak development capabilities. The plan calls
for forming three large automobile manufacturing conglomerates
that operate a dozen backbone producers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
