<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Trade Unions Pulls out of Tripartite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) Monday night pulled out of tripartite talks with the
government and employers and plans to form a workers' political
party to contest the year 2000 general elections.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was jointly made by ZCTU President Gibson
Sibanda and Secretary-General, Morgan Tsvangirayi, in Bulawayo,
the country's second largest city, the Herald newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The resolution to form a workers' party was made during a
meeting of the national working people's convention of the ZCTU in
Harare Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Our target is the 2000 election and depending on the people,
we will start working on the party in six months," Sibanda said.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of workers who filled the large city hall to capacity
agreed to the proposal by a show of hands.
</P>
<P>
Tsvangirayi said new measures to fight for workers' grievances
were needed as stayaways had outlived their usefulness.
</P>
<P>
He said the labor union would no longer participate in
tripartite negotiations as they had failed to benefit workers.
</P>
<P>
"We realized we were chasing a mirage... there is nothing at
the talks and it does not help to talk to people who are not
serious," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU resorted to stayaways last year to press for a 20
percent cost of living adjustment, removal of the development levy
and the reduction of sales tax.
</P>
<P>
The government subsequently gave in to some of the demands but
later banned stayaways through the presidential powers in
December.
</P>
<P>
Sibanda said that the ZCTU would not negotiate with the
government on a social contract as long as the ban was in force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
