<HEADLINE> Roundup: China Strives to Maintain Export Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of private Chinese
companies and 1,000 key enterprises have been granted the right to
engage in import and export related activities since 1998.
</P>
<P>
China's efforts to maintain export growth under the pressure of
the Asian financial crisis also include the introduction of
simplified application procedures enabling various large
industrial trade companies to gain foreign trade rights in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We will try a thousand and one ways to maintain a certain
growth rate for exports which have emerged as an increasingly
important factor in national economic development," said a senior
trade official with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
Developing new export growth areas, exploring new means of
trade, improving the competitive edge of Chinese commodities,
diversifying the export market, reforming the foreign trade
management system and increasing imports to a proper level will be
included in the "one thousand and one ways," according to the
official.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC has called on local trade officials and export companies
to use the advantages in their respective geographic location,
unique products and resources, and special expertise to develop
new export growth areas.
</P>
<P>
China will also encourage qualified enterprises, especially
ventures in the electronic, machinery, light industry, textile and
garments sectors to expand exports by establishing joint ventures
overseas and producing commodities using domestically manufactured
equipment, raw materials and parts.
</P>
</TEXT>
