<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Africa Trade Shows Encouraging Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Trade and investments between
Malaysia and Africa had shown encouraging results over the last
five years, Malaysian Deputy International Trade and Industry
Minister Kerk Choo Ting said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said trade between Malaysia and Africa rose from 881 million
ringgit (about 231.842 million U.S. dollars) in 1993 to 4.65
billion ringgit (about 1.223 billion dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
"Investments from Malaysia to Africa had increased from 12
million ringgit (about 3.157 million dollars) in 1992 to 115
million ringgit (about 30.263 million dollars) in 1996," he said
here at the opening of the four-day United Nations Conference on
Trade and Development (UNCTAD) Asia-Africa business networking
forum on trade and investment diversification.
</P>
<P>
Kerk said in 1997, Malaysia's investments in South Africa
amounted to 133 million ringgit (about 35 million dollars) while
the main exports to Africa were palm oil, vegetable oils and fats,
plastic products, civil engineering and contractors equipment.
</P>
<P>
He added that Malaysia's investments in Africa were mainly in
the telecommunications, hotel, banking, infrastructure and real
estate sectors.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia has always been keen on fostering and
enhancing South-South Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The forum, which is financed by the Japanese Government,
consisted of at least 25 entrepreneurs from 10 sub-Saharan African
countries.
</P>
<P>
It was aimed at facilitating trade and investments between
South Asia and sub-Sahara Africa through providing opportunities
for companies to network directly with their counterparts as well
as establishing new business contacts and promoting networking
among entrepreneurs from the two regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
