<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt. to Scrap 4,000 Posts by Year End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will
abolish over 4,000 posts in six ministries this year under the
second phase of the public service rationalization program, said
the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The move should make the civil service more efficient and cut
down on bureaucracy, the Herald newspaper Tuesday quoted the
lastest Treasury Monthly Bulletin from the Financy Ministry as
reporting.
</P>
<P>
According to the bulletin issued here Monday, the posts will
be abolished from the ministries of education, sport and culture;
mines, environment and tourism; local government and national
housing; lands and agriculture; rural resources and water
development; and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
However, Public Service Commission Public Relations Officer
Dennis Rwafa did not comment on the abolition, saying that as far
as he was concerned, draft proposals on the civil service
restructuring exercise were still before cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of economic reforms, the Zimbabwe Program for
Economic and Social Transformation started in January 1997 and is
expected to be complete by December this year.
</P>
<P>
As part of the reform, the Zimbabwean government also intends
to introduce a computerized financial management system to
overcome some of the existing problems in the management of public
finance.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry said the new system would enable it to
carry out its accounting and financial transactions for all
ministries, replacing the systems currently operated by the
Central Payments Office and Central Computing Services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
