<HEADLINE> EDS-Tibet-Hotel-Management Tibet Witnesses Improving Hotel Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Many people worried about the future
of the Lhasa Hotel in the capital of Tibet when the expiration of
a 10-year cooperative contract in August 1997 led to the departure
of managers employed by the Holiday Inn Group.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, frequent guests have since found that the current
hotel management has maintained the same level of quality service.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese possess the same hotel management skills as
foreigners," says Tibetan General Manager Jigme, adding that "the
expertise we have learned from our foreign partner established a
solid foundation for our success."
</P>
<P>
According to 57-year-old Jigme, his hotel has so far hosted
over 10,000 overseas tourists and earned record profits in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Hotels dedicated to serving foreign travelers have mushroomed
since the early 1980s, according to Tang Zhengqi, director of the
regional tourism administration.
</P>
<P>
He noted that 57 related hotels currently serving overseas
tourists are under Chinese management, with the list of managers
including quite a number of ethnic Tibetans. Related facilities
currently employ over 4,200 people.
</P>
<P>
Local managers continuously strive to improve management,
services and facilities. Their strenuous efforts have gained many
Tibetan hotels listing in travel guides published overseas.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that some 380,000 domestic and overseas
tourists have visited Tibet, with foreign exchange earnings
standing at 33.5 million U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
