<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: CPPCC Sessions, Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The First Session of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) was held in
Beijing between September 21 and 30, 1949.
</P>
<P>
It was attended by 662 representatives from all walks of life
and Mao Zedong was elected chairman of the First CPPCC National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The First Session of the Second National Committee of the CPPCC
was held in Beijing in December 1954 with 559 participants.
</P>
<P>
In September 1954, the National People's Congress, the top
legislature of the country, came into being, and hence, the CPPCC
would no longer exercise the power of the National People's
Congress (NPC), but it has continued to exist as an organization
of patriotic united front with the broadest representation.
</P>
<P>
Annual sessions of the CPPCC National Committee have been the
most solemn gathering for political consultation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The first sessions of the second, third and fourth CPPCC
national committees were held in 1954, 1959 and 1964, at which Mao
Zedong was elected honorary chairman of the national committees
and Zhou Enlai their chairman.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,988 members attended the First Session of the
Fifth CPPCC National Committee held from February 24 to March 8 in
1978. It is the first of its kind after the notorious "Great
Cultural Revolution". Deng Xiaoping was elected chairman of the
Fifth CPPCC National Committee.
</P>
<P>
The First Session of the Sixth CPPCC National Committee was
held between June 4 and 22 in 1983 in Beijing with 2,039
participants. Deng Yingchao was elected its chairperson.
</P>
<P>
The Seventh CPPCC National Committee held its first session
between March 24 and April 10, 1988 with 2,081 participants. Li
Xiannian was elected its chairman.
</P>
<P>
The First Session of the Eighth CPPCC National Committee was
held between March 14 and 27, 1993 in Beijing with 2,093
participants. It elected Li Ruihuan its chairman.
</P>
<P>
The First Session of the Ninth CPPCC National Committee was
held between March 3 and 14, 1998 in Beijing, with 2,196
participants. Li Ruihuan was re-elected its chairman.
</P>
<P>
The Second Session of the Ninth CPPCC National Committee is to
be held from March 3 through 11 this year in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Figure Skating Team out of Grand Prix final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Injuries have wiped out the
Canadian figure skating team for the Grand Prix final this week in
St. Petersburg, Russia.
</P>
<P>
The International Skating Union Monday issued a medical bye to
three-time world champion Elvis Stojko, who has been recuperating
from a groin injury since the Nagano Olympics last year.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Figure Skating Association withdrew seven-time
Canadian champion dancers Shae-Lynn Bourne and Victor Kraatz.
</P>
<P>
Stojko worried the extra wear on his body would have caused him
to lose training time before the world championships later this
month.
</P>
<P>
Bourne tore cartilage in her left knee during a freak practice
accident before the Canadian championship. She was still in pain
at the Four Continents event last week in Halifax, where she and
Kraatz won the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
After winning, Bourne said her knee felt tender. Bourne said
she did not want to jeopardize their chances at the world
championships in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
Bourne and Kraatz won the Grand Prix final in 1997, when the
event was called the Champions Series final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
