<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Government Borrows Heavily From Banks: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Poor revenue collection in
Bangladesh has forced the government to borrow heavily from the
banking system, a report in The Daily Star newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's economy failed to generate the targeted revenue
between July 1998 and January 1999, the first seven months of the
current 1998-99 fiscal year, due to prolonged flood hitting the
country from July to September 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The target could not be achieved as business activities were
heavily hampered due to countrywide prolonged floods last year,"
an official of the National Board of Revenue was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Revenue collection in the seven-month period stood at 76,218.6
million taka (1,571.52 million U.S. dollars), falling 9.54 percent
behind the targeted 84,259.2 million taka (1,737.30 million
dollars). The collection, nevertheless, was 2,922 million taka
(60.25 million dollars) higher than the corresponding period of
the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
As revenue collection slowed, the pace of government borrowing
was up.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of the current fiscal year from July
to November 1998, the government's net borrowings from banks
increase by 7,400 million taka (152.58 million dollars), up from
1,210 million taka (24.95 million dollars) of the corresponding
period of the previous fiscal year, due to rising establishment
costs and wage bills of pubic sector enterprises, high interest
payment and a rise in subsidies.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for February was worse, as the revenue would be
even lower than that in the previous months because the 28-day
month had only 14 working days, with eight weekly holidays and six
days of countrywide strike sponsored by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The shortfall might exceed 10,000 million taka (206.19 million
dollars) by the end of the fiscal year, for which the government
set a target of collecting 157,000 million taka (3,237.11 million
dollars) as revenue, according to the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
