<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Traffickers Launder Money in Thailand: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The annual U.S. report on narcotics trade claimed that Thailand
is one of 46 countries and territories which, along with America,
are primarily responsible for money laundering.
</P>
<P>
The report gave the Thai government high marks for anti-drug
efforts, saying the highlight of last year was the establishment
of an international law enforcement academy in Bangkok. The
U.S.-funded school will train lawmen from many countries to trace
and combat money laundering.
</P>
<P>
But the report revealed a new emphasis by U.S. authorities on
what they view as Thai shortcomings in trying to end the effort of
drug dealers to "wash" their money and make it appear legitimate.
</P>
<P>
The report claimed that some Thai banks continue to accept
funds which they suspect are the proceeds of drug deals "out of
fear of losing accounts."
</P>
<P>
Drug money is invested in gambling and prostitution and there
was a danger money launderers would use legal casinos to widen the
scope of their business, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
It wanted Thailand to enact its long-awaited anti-money
laundering law, noting that the Thai parliament had gutted the
proposed bill.
</P>
<P>
Washington continued to press hard for such a law. The report
said the United States has big plans once the law is in place.
</P>
<P>
The pending law is the only thing keeping Thailand out of the
1988 U.N. Drug Convention. In all other criteria Thailand is
qualified or even a regional leader, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Washington will "assist" in setting up decrees and programs to
implement the law, and then develop legal and enforcement tools,
including a strengthened conspiracy law and a Western-style
plea-bargaining system so as to allow accused criminals to plead
guilty to lesser offenses in exchange for having charges reduced,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that from 1991 to last August, Thai
authorities had seized or frozen 22 million U.S. dollars in assets
suspected to be from 439 cases of drug trafficking. Another 15
million dollars were pending in 51 other cases.
</P>
<P>
Thailand also has helped extradite both foreigners and Thais to
the United States on a variety of criminal charges, including
those related with narcotics. Last year, courts extradited five
Thais and nine foreigners to America, all with the help of
government prosecutors and the Foreign Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
