<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-24 Technical Group Meets in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Intergovernmental Group of
Twenty Four (G-24) began its Technical Group meeting Tuesday here
to discuss international monetary reforms.
</P>
<P>
Deputies representing member countries, observers, independent
researchers and related international organizations attends the
three-day meeting, Central Bank sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Technical Group is expected to concentrate on issues such
as global liquidity, the role of the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) and the World Bank (WB), said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The deliberations of the meeting will also talk about
strengthening developing countries in the World Trade
Organization, the Bank of International Settlements and its role
in international financial governance, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will form the basis of the ministerial meeting to
be held later in the year prior to the spring and annual meetings
of the IMF and the WB.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 meets twice a year at the deputies and the ministerial
level and makes proposals to the Interim Committee of the Board of
Governors of the IMF and the Development Committee of the Board of
Governors of the WB.
</P>
<P>
As a founding member of the group, Sri Lanka currently holds
the first vice chairmanship of the G-24 and will accept
chairmanship in April this year.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 consists of an important cross section of countries
across Africa, Asia and Latin America. Since its establishment in
1972 the G-24 has become the primary institutional mechanism for
the coordination of developing country positions on monetary
affairs.
</P>
<P>
The group comprises Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Cote
d'Ivoire, Egypt, Ethiopia, Gabon, Ghana, Guatemala, India, Iran,
Lebanon, Mexico, Nigeria, Pakistan, Peru, Philippines, the
Republic of Congo, Sri Lanka, Syria, Trinidad-Tobago, Venezuela
and Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
