<HEADLINE> UNPREDEP Ends Military Operations in Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Preventive
Deployment Force (UNPREDEP) has stopped all its patrols and other
military operations in Macedonia since Monday, according to
reports from Skopje.
</P>
<P>
Thousand and fifty men of the force, mainly soldiers from U.S.
and the Scandinavian countries, are waiting for new orders, some
expected to return home and others may be redeployed as part of
NATO peacekeepers in Kosovo in two months, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The UNPREDEP will also withdraw its sentry stations in the
mountain areas, armored cars and other military equipment.
</P>
<P>
The UNPREDEP was sent in to Macedonia in 1993 under UN
Resolution 743 to deter the spread of fighting to it from
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
For several times, the UN extended the force's mandate. Its
last term expired on February 28.
</P>
<P>
China on last Thursday vetoed a UN resolution to renew the
mandate for the facts that "its (Macedonia's) bilateral relations
with neighboring countries have been improved" and Macedonia "has
not been adversely affected by the conflicts in Kosovo." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
