<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Mulberry Group Proposes Election Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka government's
Mulberry Group (young radical backbenchers) has proposed election
reforms which they will discuss with President Chandrika
Kumaratunga this week, political sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Their proposal has already been referred by the president to
the Cabinet Sub-Committee on Electoral Reforms, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The group had discussions Monday with Minister of
Constitutional Affairs G.L. Pieris who praised their contribution
for coming up with a valuable proposal on the electoral system.
</P>
<P>
The issue of electoral reforms was raised following the
violence-ridden North-Western Province Council elections which
took place on January 25. The electoral system was blamed for the
escalating of election-related violence.
</P>
<P>
The Mulberry Group will also meet opposition Leader Ranil
Wickremesinghe next week to discuss their proposal.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is a combination of the present proportional
representation system and the earlier first-past-the-post system.
It will, however, do away with the preferential vote system.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft proposal, elections will be held on a
electoral division basis for 160 seats. The balance 65 seats are
to be apportioned among the contesting parties in proportion to
the aggregate of votes polled by their defeated candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
