<HEADLINE> EDS-Ningxia-Foreign Aids Foreign Aid Boosts Ningxia Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Individual income in Xihaigu, one
of China's poorest areas located in the northwestern Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region, doubled the 1995 figure to more than 1,000 yuan
(about 120 U.S. dollars) in 1998 thanks to gratis aid provided by
the World Food Program (WFP).
</P>
<P>
The goal of the WFP project centers on helping the area escape
poverty. The project helped raise the local grain output from 42
million kg in 1995 to over 70 million kg last year.
</P>
<P>
A number of other areas in Ningxia have also benefited from
foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
The region has signed 68 assistance agreements with a number of
foreign countries, including Japan, Germany, Australia, Canada and
the United States, as well as the European Union, since 1995.
Ningxia has also inked agreements with international organizations
such the United Nations Food and Agricultural Organization,
according to Regional Department of Foreign Trade.
</P>
<P>
Aid programs have not only helped reclaim farmland, harness
rivers and increase forestry coverage, but have also led to
substantial improvements in local medical care and education
services.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 40 percent of some 470 million yuan (57 million U.
S. dollars) in funding received during the period has gone for
afforestation and forest protection projects, with another 28
percent earmarked for agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
A family planning and maternal health care project funded by
Australia has provided vaccinations for more than 90 percent of
children in Xihaigu, with some 87 percent of children receiving to
prevent iodine deficiency.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 medical workers have completed training on safe
birthing methods and will provide services to some 85 percent of
expectant mothers in rural areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
