<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) is the Chinese people's patriotic
united front organization, a key institution of multi-party
cooperation and political consultations under the leadership of
the Communist Party of China (CPC), and a major form to promote
socialist democracy in China's political life.
</P>
<P>
After the victory of the War of Resistance against Japanese
Aggression in 1945, the CPC and the Kuomintang decided during
their negotiations in Chongqing to convene a political
consultative conference and organize a new government.
</P>
<P>
The conference was convened on January 10, 1946 and attended by
representatives of the Kuomintang, the CPC, the Democratic League,
the Youth Party and noted public figures. In November of the same
year, the Kuomintang unilaterally proclaimed the convention of a "
National Assembly" in violation of the resolution of the political
consultative conference and resulted in the dissolution of the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The first session of a new political consultative conference
called CPPCC was held in Beijing in September 1949, functioning as
the supreme state body.
</P>
<P>
The session adopted a "Common Program of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference" which bore the nature of a
temporary constitution, proclaimed the founding of the People's
Republic of China (PRC), elected the committee of the Central
People's Government of the PRC with Mao Zedong as its chairman,
and elected the First National Committee of the CPPCC. It also
designated the Chinese capital, national flag and national anthem,
and decided the way of numbering the years.
</P>
<P>
In September 1954, the National People's Congress, the supreme
institution of state power in China, was set up and the CPPCC then
ceased to function on the NPC's behalf. But it has continued to
exist as China's patriotic united front organization with a broad
representation and played a vital role in the country's political,
economic, cultural and social affairs and international exchanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Countries to Work Out Measures on Promoting Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Asia-Pacific countries, keen on
promoting security in the region, will work out
confidence-building measures for this purpose at a meeting to be
hosted by Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The get-together will be part of efforts by "the Intersessional
Support Group on Confidence-Building Measures" under the ASEAN
Regional Forum (ARF).
</P>
<P>
The ARF said in remarks made public on Tuesday that the meeting
will focus on enhancing trust and confidence among participants as
well as fostering an atmosphere for sustaining peace, stability
and prosperity in the region. But it did not say when the meeting
will be held.
</P>
<P>
Top of the agenda will be the overlap between
confidence-building measures and preventive diplomacy. It is
expected to come up with a recommendation for ARF ministers, who
are scheduled to meet in July in Singapore. Some AFR members want
the process to move a step closer to the second stage of
preventive diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is to be attended by more than 100 senior officials
from the foreign and defense ministers of the 21 AFR members.
These include the nine Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) as well as China, Australia, Canada, India, Mongolia,
Japan, South Korea, Papua New Guinea, New Zealand, Russia, the
United States and the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At present, the CPPCC consists of representatives of the CPC
and eight non-Communist parties, people without party affiliations,
people's organizations, and representatives from ethnic minorities
and from all social strata. In addition, there are compatriots
from the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), Macao and
Taiwan, returned overseas Chinese, and specially invited people.
</P>
<P>
The main functions of the CPPCC are political consultation,
democratic supervision and participation in and deliberation of
state affairs.
</P>
<P>
Political consultation means conferring on major policies of
central and local governments, key policy decisions concerning the
country's political, economic, cultural and social affairs before
the decisions are made, or main issues involved in the process of
carrying them out.
</P>
<P>
Democratic supervision means supervising, by means of offering
suggestions and criticism over the implementation of the China's
Constitution, relevant laws, regulations and major policies, over
the work of state organs and their functionaries.
</P>
<P>
The participation in and deliberation of state affairs means to
organize various parties, organizations, people from various
ethnic groups and social sectors to take part in the country's
political, economic, cultural and social life in various forms.
</P>
<P>
The CPPCC has a National Committee and local committees, with a
five-year term for committee members. A plenary session is held
annually.
</P>
<P>
The Second Session of the Ninth National Committee of the CPPCC,
with a total membership of 2,196, is to open in Beijing tomorrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Olympics Bidders Deny Wrongdoing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Atlanta Olympic organizers said
they did nothing wrong in the bidding 1996 Olympics, though they
admit to exceeding spending limits on gifts for IOC officials.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to International Olympic Committee president
Juan Antonio Samaranch, former Atlanta Olympics chief Billy Payne
acknoweledged that some gifts to IOC member cost more than the $
150 limit.
</P>
<P>
But he said the gifts were "within the range of customary
exchanges."
</P>
<P>
The letter, released Monday, said a local investigation found
no evidence in Atlanta's bid of improper inducements, scholarship
programs, associations with agents or excessive visits to Atlanta
by IOC members or their families.
</P>
<P>
Payne said the U.S. Olympic Committee has no plans to
investigate Atlanta's campaign to win the 1996 Games. 
</P>
