<HEADLINE> EDS-Zero Growth-Marine Output Guangdong Plans Zero Growth for Marine Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGDONG, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The south China coastal province
of Guangdong, a major producer of aquatic products, plans to
improve resources protection by maintaining zero growth for this
year's fisheries output.
</P>
<P>
Overfishing has resulted in eight consecutive seasons of
declining fish harvests in sea areas near the province and the
virtual disappearance of many desirable species such as Spanish
mackerel and large yellow croaker.
</P>
<P>
The province will continue to implement the "fishing ban" this
year as part of its effort to promote the recovery of marine
resources. The fishing ban from June 1 through July 31 will apply
to an area in the South China Sea north of 18 degrees north
latitude.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has strengthened supervision over boat engines and
plans to allocate one million yuan annually to standardize marine
fishing operations.
</P>
<P>
The province's marine industry recorded an output valued at 85
billion yuan last year. The figure, which accounted for a third of
the national total, included 5.15 million tons of aquatic products
valued at well over 40 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
