<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Enjoy Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Statistics show that some 444.5
million Chinese farmers, or 47 percent of the total rural
population, traveled to various destinations during 1998, up 15.5
percent on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
A nationwide survey revealed that rural residents spent 87.6
billion yuan (10.5 billion US dollars) on domestic travel during
in 1998, up over 50 percent on 1997. Per capita travel
expenditures grew 35 percent, with the total volume hitting 19.7
billion yuan (2.4 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The survey conducted by the National Tourists Administration
and the National Bureau of Statistics covered 24,000 rural
households throughout China, with the sole exception of the Tibet
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The survey defined travel as trips carried out for purposes
other than employment or business, with travelers using various
modes of long-distance transportation and staying at destinations
for more than 24 hours, but less than six months. The survey
excluded rural residents visiting relatives and friends within the
county and migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that domestic tourism accounts for approximately
66 percent of the nation's total tourism revenues. The large
number of potential rural travelers represents a major market for
China's tourism industry which has been adversely impacted by the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Domestic travelers generated total 1998 revenues of over 239.1
billion yuan, up 13.2 percent on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Some 694 million Chinese citizens traveled within the country
during the year, with per capita expenditures standing at 344.5
yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
