<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Ancient Relics Under Pollution Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- China's relics protection agencies
are confronted with an urgent task to rescue cultural heritage
from being damaged by suspended particles and other kinds of
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Suspended particle, some 23 million tons of which are emitted
by burning coal each year, is the biggest threat to ancient relics
across the country, said a report in today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Suspended particles have accelerated the corrosion of stone
sculptures at Yungang Grottoes in Shanxi Province, the Yaowangshan
Grottoes in Shaanxi Province, and those at the Song Tombs in Henan
Province, where most of the emperors of the Song Dynasty (960-1279)
are buried.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the China Institute of Cultural Property blamed
acid rain and sulfur dioxide for the fading or peeling of the
colorful murals and sculptures.
</P>
<P>
"Acid rain has led 500-year-old bronze astronomical instruments
in Nanjing Purple Mountain Observatory in Jiangsu Province to
corrode at four times the speed bronze normally corrodes in an
unpolluted environment", the report said.
</P>
<P>
Sulfur dioxide emitted by chemical plants within ten kilometers
of Guangsheng Temples in Shanxi Province since the 1970s has
darkened the temple's 400 square meters of frescoes and 100
colored sculptures.
</P>
<P>
Tourists visiting the relics are becoming a new source of
pollution, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Indoor temperatures and air humidity in Beijing's Forbidden
City, the Terra-cotta Warriors buildings in Shaanxi, and the Mogao
and Longmen grottoes have been raised by the dramatic increase in
visitors over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts have established an environmental monitoring
network at major relics sites since 1995 in a bid to assess
pollution damage and its causes. However, they feared that some
relics might be damaged beyond repair before they could be rescued,
the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
