<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Call up Senior Athletes for SEA Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's National Sports
Council (KONI) believes the country will have to enlist the
services of senior athletes to retain its supremacy at the 20th
Southeast Asian (SEA) Games in Bandar Seri Begawan in August.
</P>
<P>
KONI outgoing chief in charge of athletes development Mochamad
Hindarto said that topping the Games medal tally was among the
mandates from last week's meeting of the national sports community.
</P>
<P>
"It's not an easy task, however, because at about the same time
our best athletes are expected to qualify for the 2000 Olympic
Games," Hindarto was quoted by the Jakarta Post Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The SEA Games, to be held in Brunei for the first time, will
offer 235 gold medals in 21 sports. It will be held from August 7
to August 12.
</P>
<P>
Several sports federation, including the Badminton Association
of Indonesia, have called on KONI to send second-string athletes
to the Games to enable their seniors to focus on the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Competition for Olympic berths will also start in August for
several sports.
</P>
<P>
Hindarto insisted one event would not be sacrificed for the
other.
</P>
<P>
"We consider the two events equally important, so we have to
excel in both," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hindarto said KONI could not send second stringers to the SEA
Games due to limited preparation time.
</P>
<P>
Recruiting talent from training centers nationwide will be
another option for KONI to select athletes for the SEA Games, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia will compete in 20 sports of badminton, basketball,
billiards and snooker, bowling, boxing, cycling, soccer, golf,
hockey, karate, pencak silat (k.o. system of self-defense), sepak
takraw, shooting, squash, swimming, table tennis, taekwondo,
tennis, track and field and traditional boat racing.
</P>
<P>
It will give a miss to bowls, virtually unknown in the world's
fourth most populated country. 
</P>
