<HEADLINE> Cambodian Assembly Debates Bill to Create Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia National Assembly
began to debate a constitutional amendment Tuesday to pave the way
for the creation of a controversial and long-awaited Senate.
</P>
<P>
Assembly's President Prince Norodom Ranariddh presided over the
special session. 112 out of 122 parliamentarians attended the
session, but Sam Rainsy, president of his self-named opposition
party, is not present.
</P>
<P>
If the amendment is passed as drafted, the 61-member Senate,
headed by Cambodian People's Party (CPP) President Chea Sim, would
function as an institution reviewing assembly legislation and act
as a coordinator between the Council of Ministers and the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The agreement to create the Senate was reached by FUNCINPEC and
CPP in November last year as a part of the compromise to form the
new coalition government after months of post-election deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Hun Sen said earlier that he expects the Senate
will be formed by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
The failure to create the Senate was cited as a reason for
Cambodia's delay admission into the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
The Senate is expected to comprise 61 members, among them two
will be nominated by the King and two others are appointed by the
assembly, while the rest are elected from the three political
parties who have seats in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
It was said that 30 senate members are to be nominated by CPP,
20 by FUNCINPEC party and seven by the opposition Sam Rainsy
Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
