<HEADLINE> Less Than Half Indonesian Parties Meet Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Less than 50 percent of the 141
political parties seeking to participate in the upcoming general
election in Indonesia have completed documents required under the
political laws signed by President B.J. Habibie last month.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Election Institute said that less than 50
percent of the parties hoping to compete in the general election
were able to submit a completed set of papers by Monday's 4:00
p.m. (local time) deadline.
</P>
<P>
Just a few minutes before the deadline, only 38 parties had
completed their registration documents and were ready to be
assessed by Team-11, the Indonesian Observer Tuesday quoted the
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The so-call independent Team-11 has been tasked by the
government to assess which parties are eligible to contest the
election.
</P>
<P>
The new political laws determine that political parties
eligible to take part in the June 7 general election must have
chapters in at least nine provinces with executive boards, as well
as having regional boards in at least 50 percent of the provinces'
regencies or municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The June election will elect a new House of Representatives,
whose members will be part of the 700-strong People's Consultative
Assembly, the nation's highest legislative body, which will select
the next president. 
