<HEADLINE> Qingdao Port Attracts More Foreign Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Port of Qingdao, one of China'
s major seaports located in Shandong Province, has emerged as a
magnet for foreign investment in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Some 10-odd multinational companies have established joint
ventures with the port and half of the world's top 20 shipping
companies have opened representative offices.
</P>
<P>
The port and the Orient Overseas Group from Hong Kong recently
established a container shipping joint venture with a total
investment of 78.85 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jingyu, president of the Orient Overseas (China)
Investment Ltd., said the group was attracted by Qingdao's
prospects for becoming an international shipping center.
</P>
<P>
The Port of Qingdao, which consists of 14 docks and 70 berths,
has established business ties with some 450 foreign ports.
</P>
<P>
The port is the largest ore depot in north China, as well as
the nation's major crude oil depot, second largest container
shipping port and fifth largest coal port. The port's freight
volume has grown by an average of 10 million tons annually over
the past few years.  
</P>
