<HEADLINE> U.S. British Bombing Blocks UN Humanitarian Program in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and British bombing
raids are blocking distribution of food, medicine and other
supplies in the northern part of Iraq, a U.N. official said here
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Hans von Sponeck, the Baghdad-based U.N.
coordinator of the "oil-for-food" program, said: "We had to take a
number of measures to react to this deterioration of the security
situation in Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Sponeck said, between 11 a.m. and 3 p.m. trucks no longer
ferried supplies there because that was usually the time of
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Overnight stays by U.N. monitors had also been curtailed and
that one staff member had resigned because of the pressure of the
attacks, he added.
</P>
<P>
"In a nutshell, what is happening right now is a certain
shrinking in the amount of freedom that we have to move our goods
and to move our people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Right now we are continuing to do our work fairly much as it
is expected from us. But if the frequency and damages continue and
increase, then we have to rethink," he added.
</P>
<P>
The airstrikes are carried out mainly in the Western-imposed no-
fly zone in northern Iraq.  
</P>
</TEXT>
