<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Section of Yellow River Dry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 2 (Xinhua) -- As of today, a section of the
Yellow River, the second longest in China, in central China's
Henan Province, has been dry for 24 days.
</P>
<P>
The dry-up was caused by a reduced water flow into the middle
reaches in recent weeks, and the increased use of water for
farmland after a long spell of drought at the lower reaches.
</P>
<P>
The country's water conservation departments have ordered the
controlled use of water to alleviate water shortages at the lower
reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River originates in northwestern Qinghai Province
and runs through nine provinces or autonomous regions to a total
length of 5,464 kilometers. Sustained drought since 1990 has led
to a sharp decrease of water flow in the upper reaches, causing
some sections of the river to go dry in the lower reaches,
affecting the economic expansion of the river valley. Sections of
the Yellow River dried up for as long as 226 days in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tree Rings to Offer Climate Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Growth ring samples from trees
growing on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau at 4,500 meters above sea
level have enabled Chinese scientists to study the history of the
plateau's climate.
</P>
<P>
The study was listed as one of the major breakthroughs in basic
research during 1998, according to sources from the Ministry of
Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
A group of scientists led by Kang Xingcheng, a researcher with
the Lanzhou Institute of Glaciology and Cryopedology (study of
frozen earth) under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS),
obtained the samples from a cypress grove in the Yarlung Zangbo
River Valley.
</P>
<P>
Scientists note that growth rings, or so-called "dictionaries
of natural history", provide information about environmental and
climatic changes.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary studies of the growth rings showed the cypress
trees are approximately 500 years old. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
