<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bolivian Life Expectancy Grows from 60 to 62 years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
La Paz, March 1 (Xinhua)-- The life expectancy of Bolivians
grew from 60 to 62 years, while the rates of mortality diminished
between 1994 and 1998, according to a national study of demography
and health.
</P>
<P>
DHS Macro International and the National Institute of
Statistics (INE) of Bolivia published Monday a report saying that
during this period the Bolivian population grew from 7.2 to 7.9
million, of which the 62 percent live in cities, while the rate of
mortality diminished from twelve to nine individuals for every
thousand inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
Illiteracy diminished among those over 15 years old from 20 to
14 percent, with significant differences between sexes; from 28 to
20 percent among women and from 12 to 7 percent among men. The
rate of child mortality decreased from 75 to 67 children for one
thousand born alive, and the percentage of attention to mothers
and newly born children rose in the last four years from 52 to 69
percent, added the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
