<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Still Expects Libyan Response on Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 1 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said on Monday that he is yet to receive an official Libyan
response to his letter on the trial of the two Libyans in the
December 1988 bombing of a Pan Am airliner, which killed 270
people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon his arrival at the U.N. headquarters
on Monday morning, Annan said, "I haven't heard from the Libyan
authorities yet."
</P>
<P>
"As you know, I wrote to them. I am expecting a formal
communication from them. In the absence of communication I cannot
comment authoritatively on their response," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan wrote to Tripoli last week to offer what he said "all
explanations and clarifications necessary" at the request of the
Libyan authorities, and he told reporters last week that "the next
stage" is up to Libya to make a decision on surrendering the two
Libyan suspects.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Libya said that it could not accept a time limit
set by the United States and Britain to hand over the two
suspects.
</P>
<P>
Those making the demands "do not really want to conduct a fair
trial," a Libyan foreign ministry official said on Saturday in the
capital Tripoli, "It is not possible to discuss a deadline before
an agreement on the arrangement and the guarantees that had been
demanded by Libya."
</P>
<P>
Washington and London warned Libya on Friday it had 30 days
to deliver the two men to be tried by a Scottish court in the
Netherlands. However, the two countries stopped short of saying
what could happen if Libya refused.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan permanent representative to the United Nations,
Abuzed Omar Dorda, said that full Security Council had not issued
an ultimatum. He said Tripoli still wanted U.N. sanctions lifted
rather than suspended in exchange for any surrender of the two
suspects.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council completed its four-month review of its
sanctions against Libya on Friday without discussing or making
any changes.
</P>
<P>
A Security Council resolution, adopted in August last year,
calls for an automatic suspension of the sanctions once the two
suspects have arrived in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Libya in August last year accepted a U.S.-U.K. proposal to have
the two suspects tried before a Scottish court in the Netherlands,
but later Libya was locked in a dispute with the U.S. and Britain
on the place where the two suspects, if convicted, are to serve
their sentences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eurozone Money Supply Expands Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The supply of money in the 11-nation
Eurozone jumped sharply in the first month of 1999, showing a 5.7
percent annual growth rate, the European Central Bank said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The rise for the broad-based M3 supply was due to an 18.3
percent surge in the annual growth rate for overnight loans, a
report of the bank said.
</P>
<P>
In December, the money supply growth rate had been 4.5 percent,
with overnight money expanding at an 11.4 percent clip.
</P>
<P>
For the three-month period November 1998-January 1999, the
money supply growth averaged 4.9 percent, up 0.2 percentage points
from the October-December period.
</P>
<P>
The M3 supply consists of cash in circulation, fixed deposits
under four years and savings deposits with mandatory withdrawal
period.
</P>
<P>
The countries of the 11-nation Eurozone are all 15 European
Union members except for Britain, Sweden, Denmark and Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
