<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Business Failures Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain recorded a significant
increase in the level of business failures last year, according to
a survey by business information specialists Dun &AMP; Bradstreet.
</P>
<P>
More than 38,000 UK businesses went bankrupt in 1998, an
increase of 6.2 percent compared to the previous year. It was the
first increase in six years, since the UK's last recession in
1992.
</P>
<P>
In the rest of Europe, business failures fell by 7.8 percent,
with Norway, Portugal, and Ireland the only countries with big
increases.
</P>
<P>
Another Dun &AMP; Bradstreet survey of 10,000 European company
managers showed that business confidence was at its lowest level
for five years.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that those two surveys provide evidence
that Britain is further ahead in the worsening economic cycle than
the rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
Philip Mellor of Dun &AMP; Bradstreet said: "Despite the latest
cuts in interest rates we do not anticipate any improvement in the
rate of business failures until the latter half of this year."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
