<HEADLINE> European Socialist Party Congress Opens in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Congress of the European
Socialist Party opened Monday in the northern Italian city of
Milan to prepare for the mid-June European elections.
</P>
<P>
In the first European elections after the debut of euro in 11
European Union countries, the final victory between the Socialists
and the People's Party could depend on a handful of seats. In the
outgoing European Parliament, the Socialists have 214 out of 626
seats while the European People's Party has 202.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest polls, the People's Party is growing in
strength in several of the big EU nations governed by Socialists.
</P>
<P>
In Milan Monday, the president of the European Socialist Party
and the German defense minister, Rudolf Sharping, accused the
People's Party of being "a factor of instability" for EU policy
"because of the internal divisions between Federalists and
nationalists.
</P>
<P>
European caucus leader Pauline Green said "our adversaries in
Europe say they want to become the number one group in the
European Parliament but, by now, they no longer have significant
weight among the EU governments" and their guidance at the head of
the European Commission has been disastrous, she said.
</P>
<P>
The present president of the European Commission is Jacques
Santer, former head of the European People's Party in Luxembourg.
This is the first time he has been so sharply attacked by the
Socialist caucus leader who two months ago helped avert a censure
motion against Santer in Strasbourg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990302.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lafontaine Warns Firms Not to Leave Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Reacting to threats of a corporate
exodus from Germany due to taxes, German Finance Minister Oskar
Lafontaine warned Monday it could become difficult for
non-resident concerns to do business with German clients.
</P>
<P>
"I would advise the insurance sector -- every company -- to
consider if they were to turn up as insurance providers, based on
who knows where, whether they will have the same business in
Germany as now," said Lafontaine at a news briefing, according to
a report of the German Press Press Agency.
</P>
<P>
"And I do not want to say anything more about this," said
Lafontaine, who dismissed threats by several major German
companies to leave Germany due to his tax plans as "not credible."
</P>
<P>
The Munich-based Allianz insurance has said it could move its
entire headquarters out of Germany. Allianz employs 34,000 people
in Germany and is one of the biggest insurance companies
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The Essen-based energy giant RWE says Lafontaine's tax reforms
will cost it 4.8 billion dollars in extra taxes in the coming four
years.
</P>
<P>
Given recent liberalization of Europe's energy market, RWE is
now thinking about making future major investments abroad, said
company spokesman Dieter Schweer in an interview with the Bild
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine said, however, this would not protect the company
from paying German taxes. "In the end they earn their money here
if we are talking about energy concerns," he added.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine rejected claims by the energy sector that his plans
would cost it a total of 14.5 billion dollars in new taxes.
</P>
<P>
This is "utterly wrong," said Lafontaine.
</P>
<P>
But when asked how much his tax plans would cost the energy
sector, Lafontaine admitted he did not know.
</P>
<P>
"I do not learn all the figures and at least 1,000 play a role
here," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Paying taxes is not a reprehensible state of affairs or an
affront of democracy," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
