<HEADLINE> Canada to Support Demining project in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Monday that the
Canadian International Development Agency (CIDA) will support a
project in Mozambique to help Mozambican people to remove
landmines from their lands.
</P>
<P>
The CIDA will undertake a national minefield survey as part of
the CIDA's support for demining in Mozambique. The survey will
identify and map all suspected mined areas. Policy-makers and
field experts, in Mozambique, will be able to use the survey to
make priority decisions on where to assign landmine awareness
teams and where to begin landmine removal.
</P>
<P>
The CIDA will provide 1.7 million Canadian dollars (1.12
million U.S. dollars) for this initiative, which is part of the
Canadian Landmine Fund announced in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has approximately 1 million landmines. This threat
to human lives has paralyzed economic activities in many parts of
the country, which is one of the poorest in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
